"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/620016","Home Office","false","2016-12-12","<p>We keep all fees under regular review.</p>","Scarborough and Whitby","Mr Robert Goodwill",,"2016-12-12T13:36:13.367Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/620016/answer","Biography information for Mr Robert Goodwill","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/620016/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/620016/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2016-10-24","Naturalisation: EEA Nationals","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, what assessment she has made of the potential merits of reducing the fees for naturalisation applications from EEA nationals as a result of the EU referendum.","false","Biography information for Richard Fuller","Bedford","Richard Fuller","49855"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/620017","Home Office","false","2016-11-01","<p>Dame Louise Casey’s independent review on boosting opportunity and integration in isolated and vulnerable communities will report to the Prime Minister and be published in due course.</p>","Truro and Falmouth","Sarah Newton",,"2016-11-01T16:22:55.76Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/620017/answer","Biography information for Sarah Newton","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/620017/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/620017/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2016-10-24","Community Relations","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, when her Department plans to publish the results of Dame Louise Casey's review into opportunity and integration in some of the UK's most isolated communities.","false","Biography information for Mr Ranil Jayawardena","North East Hampshire","Mr Ranil Jayawardena","49843"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/620018","Home Office","false","2016-11-03","<p>This Government is committed to tackling hate crime. The UK has one of the strongest legislative frameworks in the world to tackle hate crime. We are working across Government with police, (including National Community Tensions Team), the Crown Prosecution Service and community partners to send out a clear message that hate crime will not be tolerated and we will vigorously pursue and prosecute those who commit these crimes.</p><p>The Home Office publish detailed hate crime statistics, including by force, each year, but these cannot be broken down by month. The most recently published statistics for 2015/16 are available at:</p><p>https://www.gov.uk/government/statistics/hate-crime-england-and-wales-2015-to-2016</p><p>This release also included an Annex of provisional data for specific racially and religiously aggravated offences between April and August 2016 in England and Wales.</p>","Truro and Falmouth","Sarah Newton",,"2016-11-03T17:52:56.11Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/620018/answer","Biography information for Sarah Newton","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/620018/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/620018/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2016-10-24","Hate Crime: West Yorkshire","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, how many (a) racially and (b) religiously motivated offences were recorded by West Yorkshire Police in June, July and August (i) 2016 and (ii) 2015.","false","Biography information for Mary Creagh","Wakefield","Mary Creagh","49859"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/620019","Home Office","false","2016-11-01","<p>The Disclosure and Barring Service regularly publishes data on police force performance, which can be located through the following link:</p><p>https://www.gov.uk/government/statistics/dbs-dataset-5-police-disclosure-unit-performance</p><p>I visited the Metropolitan Police Service disclosure unit on 2 September. I regularly receive reports from the Disclosure and Barring Service on the performance of the Metropolitan Police Service. I have made it clear that delays must be addressed. The Disclosure and Barring Service is working with the Metropolitan Police Service to reduce turnaround times as quickly as possible, which includes additional funding, staff and training, process improvement and support from other forces.</p>","Truro and Falmouth","Sarah Newton",,"2016-11-01T16:23:15.297Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/620019/answer","Biography information for Sarah Newton","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/620019/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/620019/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2016-10-24","Vetting","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, what assessment she has made of Metropolitan Police Service performance against the terms set out in its service level agreement with the Disclosure and Barring Service.","false","Biography information for Richard Fuller","Bedford","Richard Fuller","49865"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/620020","Ministry of Justice","false","2016-11-01","<p>Immigration advisers must be registered with the Office of the Immigration Services Commissioner (OISC) or a member of an approved professional body, for example, the Law Society. The OISC protects customers by setting robust standards for registration, ensuring advisers are fit and competent and act in the best interests of their clients. It is responsible for investigating complaints about registered advisers and investigating and prosecuting those who are providing immigration advice illegally.</p>","North East Hertfordshire","Sir Oliver Heald",,"2016-11-01T17:53:58.34Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/620020/answer","Biography information for Sir Oliver Heald","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/620020/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/620020/answer",,,,,"54","Justice","Justice","2016-10-24","Immigration: Advisory Services","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Justice, what recent steps her Department has taken to stop rogue solicitors and legal advisers from offering immigration advice.","false","Biography information for Vicky Foxcroft","Lewisham, Deptford","Vicky Foxcroft","49875"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/620021","Home Office","false","2016-11-03","<p>A citizen of the UK, encompassing Great Britain and Northern Ireland, is regarded as a British citizen. British citizens are not required to complete a landing card when arriving at UK airports from European Union destinations or anywhere else.</p>","Scarborough and Whitby","Mr Robert Goodwill",,"2016-11-03T17:46:15.973Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/620021/answer","Biography information for Mr Robert Goodwill","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/620021/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/620021/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2016-10-24","Immigration Controls","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, whether it is the policy of her Department to require completion of immigration cards by UK citizens arriving at UK airports from EU destinations.","false","Biography information for Dr Paul Monaghan","Caithness, Sutherland and Easter Ross","Dr Paul Monaghan","49863"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/620022","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2016-10-27","<p>The following projects are funded from the Conflict, Security and Stability Fund (CSSF) during the current financial year (2016/17).</p><p>- Small training team as part of the United States Security Coordinator to provide institutional development and professionalisation of the Palestinian Authority Security Forces</p><p>- Technical assistance to the Palestinian Ministry of Interior (MOI) to improve its capability to provide oversight and management of the security services</p><p>- Support to EU Coordinating Office for Palestinian Police Support</p><p>- Empowerment of young Israeli leaders to strengthen support for peace in their communities</p><p>- UK-Israel Informal Security Dialogue</p><p>- Legal Aid and Settlement Monitoring in the West Bank.</p>","Bournemouth East","Mr Tobias Ellwood",,"2016-10-27T13:49:09.573Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/620022/answer","Biography information for Mr Tobias Ellwood","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/620022/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/620022/answer",,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2016-10-24","Middle East: Conflict, Stability and Security Fund","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Foreign and Commonwealth Affairs, which projects in Israel and the Occupied Palestinian Territories receive funding through the Conflict, Stability and Security Fund.","true","Biography information for Joan Ryan","Enfield North","Joan Ryan","49936"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/620023","Department for International Development","false","2016-10-31","<p>Energy Africa aims to develop compacts with up to 14 African countries to remove policy and regulatory barriers to off-grid solar market expansion. Eleven countries (Ethiopia, Ghana, Kenya, Malawi, Mozambique, Nigeria, Rwanda, Senegal, Sierra Leone, Somalia and Uganda) have signed interim partnership agreements. The compact development process is well under way in these countries and one has been agreed with Sierra Leone. Several others are in final negotiations and are expected to be agreed in the coming months.</p><p>DFID is also providing technical assistance and other programmatic support to help with the implementation of the compacts.</p>","Stockton South","James Wharton",,"2016-10-31T16:33:16.74Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/620023/answer","Biography information for James Wharton","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/620023/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/620023/answer",,,,,"20","International Development","International Development","2016-10-24","Africa: Electricity","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for International Development, what recent progress has been made on the Energy Africa access campaign.","false","Biography information for Richard Graham","Gloucester","Richard Graham","49932"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/620024","Department for International Development","false","2016-10-27","<p>DFID’s current bilateral programme covering the Occupied Palestinian Territories does not directly support any Israeli or Palestinian Non-Governmental Organisations (NGOs). DFID indirectly funds Palestinian and Israeli NGOs through our support to an access to justice programme benefiting women and implemented by UN agencies, and a private sector development programme implemented through Development Alternatives Incorporated (DAI).</p>","Penrith and The Border","Rory Stewart",,"2016-10-27T14:54:33.153Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/620024/answer","Biography information for Rory Stewart","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/620024/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/620024/answer",,,,,"20","International Development","International Development","2016-10-24","Middle East: Overseas Aid","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for International Development, which (a) Israeli and (b) Palestinian non-governmental organisations and projects receive how much funding from her Department.","true","Biography information for Joan Ryan","Enfield North","Joan Ryan","49937"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/620025","Department for International Development","false","2016-10-31","<p>UK funds are being dispersed to support post-earthquake reconstruction activities primarily in four focal districts; which are Gorkha, Dhading, Rasuwa and Nuwakot. The UK Government is also supporting the Government of Nepal’s national reconstruction priorities that help reach out to all earthquake affected districts. These include housing reconstruction coordination, assessing geological post-earthquake hazards, enrolling affected households into the housing grant process, and training builders.</p><p>DFID works hard to ensure that all of our programmes are closely monitored, and adopts a zero tolerance approach towards any form of corruption and fraud. A DFID field office in the earthquake affected areas and field visits from DFID staff monitor our partners’ delivery. All DFID reconstruction related projects have been designed with key stakeholders as well as being informed by surveys, field visits and studies conducted in the aftermath of the earthquake.</p>","Penrith and The Border","Rory Stewart",,"2016-10-31T18:13:18.44Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/620025/answer","Biography information for Rory Stewart","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/620025/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/620025/answer",,,,,"20","International Development","International Development","2016-10-24","Nepal: Earthquakes","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for International Development, to which areas UK funds to help with the earthquake in Nepal are being dispersed; and what steps she is taking to ensure the resources are reaching the affected areas.","false","Biography information for Nick Smith","Blaenau Gwent","Nick Smith","49934"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/620026","Ministry of Justice","true","2016-11-01","<p>The numbers of recalls of offenders for absconding from Approved Premises between 2010/11 and 2015/16, in England and in Wales, are set out below.</p><p> </p><table><tbody><tr><td><p> </p></td><td><p>England</p></td><td><p>Wales</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2010/11</p></td><td><p>1153</p></td><td><p>45</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2011/12</p></td><td><p>986</p></td><td><p>27</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2012/13</p></td><td><p>911</p></td><td><p>41</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2013/14</p></td><td><p>836</p></td><td><p>31</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2014/15</p></td><td><p>753</p></td><td><p>33</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2015/16</p></td><td><p><del class="ministerial">662</del><ins class="ministerial">884</ins></p></td><td><p><del class="ministerial">21</del><ins class="ministerial">27</ins></p></td></tr></tbody></table><p> </p><p> </p><p>Public protection is our top priority. When an abscond takes place, the offender is recalled, and the Police are notified and are responsible for locating the offender.</p><p> </p><p>We take any breach of licence conditions extremely seriously and offenders who abscond can be sent back to prison.</p>","East Surrey","Mr Sam Gyimah",,"2016-11-01T17:33:34.793Z","2016-12-22T11:46:38.03Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/620026/answer","Biography information for Mr Sam Gyimah","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/620026/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/620026/answer","East Surrey","Mr Sam Gyimah","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/620026/answer/previousversion/17832","Biography information for Mr Sam Gyimah","54","Justice","Justice","2016-10-24","Bail Hostels","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Justice, how many offenders absconded from bail hostels in (a) England and (b) Wales in each year since 2010.","false","Biography information for David Hanson","Delyn","Mr David Hanson","49987"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/620027","Ministry of Justice","false","2016-11-01","<p>The information requested is not held centrally and could only be obtained at disproportionate cost.</p><p> </p>","East Surrey","Mr Sam Gyimah","49989","2016-11-01T17:39:11.837Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/620027/answer","Biography information for Mr Sam Gyimah","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/620027/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/620027/answer",,,,,"54","Justice","Justice","2016-10-24","Electronic Tagging","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Justice, how many requests from the probation service have been made for offenders to be fitted with electronic tags in each year since 2010.","false","Biography information for David Hanson","Delyn","Mr David Hanson","49988"
