"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/620029","HM Treasury","false","2016-10-27","<p>HM Revenue &amp; Customs (HMRC) does not break down statistics for tobacco prosecutions to separate out those solely resulting from smuggling activity. Total prosecutions for tobacco offences for the last complete five years for which figures are available were as follows:</p><p> </p><p> </p><table><tbody><tr><td><p><strong>Financial Year</strong></p></td><td><p><strong>Convictions</strong></p></td><td><p><strong>Acquittals</strong></p></td><td><p><strong>Total Prosecutions</strong> <strong>(Convictions + Acquittals)</strong></p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2011/12</p></td><td><p>156</p></td><td><p>9</p></td><td><p>165</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2012/13</p></td><td><p>159</p></td><td><p>10</p></td><td><p>169</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2013/14</p></td><td><p>261</p></td><td><p>15</p></td><td><p>276</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2014/15</p></td><td><p>237</p></td><td><p>26</p></td><td><p>263</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2015/16</p></td><td><p>268</p></td><td><p>26</p></td><td><p>294</p></td></tr></tbody></table><p> </p><p> </p><p>The figures for previous years are not available, as they belong to the prosecuting authorities and are not on a comparable basis.</p><p> </p>","Battersea","Jane Ellison",,"2016-10-27T13:45:27.75Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/620029/answer","Biography information for Jane Ellison","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/620029/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/620029/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2016-10-24","Tobacco: Smuggling","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, how many prosecutions there have been for tobacco smuggling in each of the last 10 years.","false","Biography information for Tim Loughton","East Worthing and Shoreham","Tim Loughton","50019"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/620030","Ministry of Justice","true","2016-11-01","<p>The National Offender Management Service records offenders who have been returned to custody from Approved Premises under seven categories: absconding, breaches of the Approved Premises Rules, positive drugs tests, increasing risk, breaches of licence conditions, breaches of curfew restrictions, and other reasons. All recalls to custody involve the police, since only they have the legal power to return offenders to custody.</p><p> </p><p>The numbers of recalls for any of these reasons between 2011/12 and 2015/16, in England and in Wales, are set out below. These include figures for breach of curfew and absconding, as provided in answer to questions 49931 and 49987 respectively.</p><table><tbody><tr><td><p> </p></td><td><p>England</p></td><td><p>Wales</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2010/11</p></td><td><p>2445</p></td><td><p>106</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2011/12</p></td><td><p>2413</p></td><td><p>115</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2012/13</p></td><td><p>2339</p></td><td><p>112</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2013/14</p></td><td><p>2346</p></td><td><p>109</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2014/15</p></td><td><p>2467</p></td><td><p>115</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2015/16</p></td><td><p><del class="ministerial">2125</del><ins class="ministerial">2807</ins></p></td><td><p><del class="ministerial">110</del><ins class="ministerial">143</ins></p></td></tr></tbody></table>","East Surrey","Mr Sam Gyimah",,"2016-11-01T17:30:40.573Z","2016-12-22T11:46:21.747Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/620030/answer","Biography information for Mr Sam Gyimah","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/620030/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/620030/answer","East Surrey","Mr Sam Gyimah","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/620030/answer/previousversion/17831","Biography information for Mr Sam Gyimah","54","Justice","Justice","2016-10-24","Bail Hostels","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Justice, how many offenders housed in bail hostels have been taken back into custody as a result of notification from bail hostel staff to police in each year since 2010.","false","Biography information for David Hanson","Delyn","Mr David Hanson","50040"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/620031","Ministry of Justice","false","2016-10-27","<p>The available information for prison education is published by the Department for Education (DfE) in their Statistical First Release, available on gov.uk.</p>","East Surrey","Mr Sam Gyimah",,"2016-10-27T14:12:51.137Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/620031/answer","Biography information for Mr Sam Gyimah","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/620031/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/620031/answer",,,,,"54","Justice","Justice","2016-10-24","Prisons: Education","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Justice, what the completion rate was for education courses taken in prisons in each of the last five years.","false","Biography information for Stephen Timms","East Ham","Stephen Timms","49948"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/620032","Ministry of Justice","true","2016-11-01","<p>The National Offender Management Service records only those breaches of curfew restrictions from Probation Approved Premises where offenders are recalled to custody as a result. Curfew breaches, while important, do not necessarily lead to recall. For example, an offender may be only a few minutes late, or may have been unable to return for reasons outside his or her control. In such cases other action may be appropriate instead.</p><p> </p><p>97% of Approved Premises residents complete their time at the Approved Premises without breaching their curfew. The numbers of recalls for breach of curfew between 2011/12 and 2015/16, in England and in Wales, are set out below. Curfew was not recorded separately from other recall reasons in 2010/11.</p><table><tbody><tr><td><p> </p></td><td><p>England</p></td><td><p>Wales</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2011/12</p></td><td><p>205</p></td><td><p>2</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2012/13</p></td><td><p>211</p></td><td><p>1</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2013/14</p></td><td><p>230</p></td><td><p>0</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2014/15</p></td><td><p>240</p></td><td><p>2</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2015/16</p></td><td><p><del class="ministerial">234</del><ins class="ministerial">292</ins></p></td><td><p><del class="ministerial">11</del><ins class="ministerial">16</ins></p></td></tr></tbody></table><p> </p><p>Public protection is our top priority. When an abscond takes place, police are immediately notified and are responsible for locating the offender. We take any breach of licence conditions extremely seriously and offenders who abscond can be sent back to prison.</p>","East Surrey","Mr Sam Gyimah",,"2016-11-01T17:36:44.863Z","2016-12-22T11:46:50.437Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/620032/answer","Biography information for Mr Sam Gyimah","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/620032/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/620032/answer","East Surrey","Mr Sam Gyimah","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/620032/answer/previousversion/17834","Biography information for Mr Sam Gyimah","54","Justice","Justice","2016-10-24","Bail Hostels","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Justice, how many offenders have been in breach of curfew conditions at bail hostels in (a) England and (b) Wales in each year since 2010.","false","Biography information for David Hanson","Delyn","Mr David Hanson","49931"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/620033","Ministry of Justice","false","2016-11-01","<p>The information requested is not held centrally and could only be obtained at disproportionate cost.</p>","North East Hertfordshire","Sir Oliver Heald",,"2016-11-01T17:54:06.727Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/620033/answer","Biography information for Sir Oliver Heald","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/620033/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/620033/answer",,,,,"54","Justice","Justice","2016-10-24","Immigration: Appeals","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Justice, how many appeals to the First Tier Tribunal (Immigration and Asylum) have been awaiting allocation of a hearing for more than (a) six months and (b) twelve months in the last three years for which figures are available.","false","Biography information for Richard Fuller","Bedford","Richard Fuller","49930"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/620034","Ministry of Justice","false","2016-11-01","<p>Prisons should be places of safety and reform. Improving safety and decreasing violence is an urgent priority for the Government.</p><p> </p><p>Earlier in October the Justice Secretary announced that funding of £14million will be given to 10 prisons with some of the highest rates of violence. This will provide for additional staff to implement new offender management arrangements, including dedicated prisoner contact time.</p><p> </p><p>We will be setting out our plans for prison safety and reform in a White Paper in the coming weeks, including our plans to reduce prison violence.</p>","East Surrey","Mr Sam Gyimah",,"2016-11-01T15:27:15.287Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/620034/answer","Biography information for Mr Sam Gyimah","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/620034/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/620034/answer",,,,,"54","Justice","Justice","2016-10-24","Prisons: Crimes of Violence","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Justice, what recent steps her Department has taken to tackle the rise in incidents of violence in male prisons.","false","Biography information for Vicky Foxcroft","Lewisham, Deptford","Vicky Foxcroft","49871"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/620035","Department of Health","false","2016-11-01","<p>Young offenders are entitled to the same range and quality of health care treatments, including mental health care, as people in the community.</p><p> </p><p>The Department is committed to improving mental health treatment for young people in contact with the youth justice system, including those who are vulnerable to self-harm and suicide attempts. NHS England is developing a specific £24 million programme to improve mental health provision for children and young people, under 18 years old, in contact with the justice system.</p>","Oxford West and Abingdon","Nicola Blackwood",,"2016-11-01T16:55:16.927Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/620035/answer","Biography information for Baroness Blackwood of North Oxford","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/620035/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/620035/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2016-10-24","Young Offenders: Mental Health Services","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, what steps are being taken to improve access to mental health services for young offenders.","false","Biography information for Vicky Foxcroft","Lewisham, Deptford","Vicky Foxcroft","49872"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/620036","Ministry of Justice","false","2016-10-28","<p>We are considering the adequacy of young offender institutions as part of our plans to transform the prison estate. We are investing £1.3 billion to reform and modernise the prison estate to make it more efficient, safer and focused on supporting prisoner rehabilitation.</p>","Bracknell","Dr Phillip Lee",,"2016-10-28T12:12:00.373Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/620036/answer","Biography information for Dr Phillip Lee","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/620036/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/620036/answer",,,,,"54","Justice","Justice","2016-10-24","Young Offender Institutions","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Justice, what assessment her Department has made of the adequacy of the living conditions in young offender institutes.","false","Biography information for Vicky Foxcroft","Lewisham, Deptford","Vicky Foxcroft","49873"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/620037","Ministry of Justice","false","2016-11-01","<p>HM Courts &amp; Tribunals Service (HMCTS) has provided an additional 4,500 tribunal sitting days for the First Tier Tribunal (Immigration and Asylum Chamber) in this financial year compared to 2015/16. HMCTS keeps performance and resource levels under close review. The Government has also recently published a consultation on expediting appeals from immigration detainees.</p>","North East Hertfordshire","Sir Oliver Heald",,"2016-11-01T17:53:51.12Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/620037/answer","Biography information for Sir Oliver Heald","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/620037/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/620037/answer",,,,,"54","Justice","Justice","2016-10-24","Immigration: Appeals","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Justice, what steps she is taking to reduce waiting times for the First Tier Tribunal (Immigration and Asylum).","false","Biography information for Richard Fuller","Bedford","Richard Fuller","49852"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/620038","Prime Minister","false","2016-10-27","<p>Details of Ministerial UK official visits and official meetings with external organisations and individuals are published quarterly and made available on the gov.uk website.</p><p> </p>","Maidenhead","Mrs Theresa May",,"2016-10-27T11:41:15.323Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/620038/answer","Biography information for Mrs Theresa May","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/620038/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/620038/answer",,,,,"23","Prime Minister","Prime Minister","2016-10-24","Food Banks","1","House of Commons","To ask the Prime Minister, (a) how many and (b) which food banks she has visited since becoming Prime Minister.","false","Biography information for Mr David Winnick","Walsall North","Mr David Winnick","49826"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/620039","Home Office","false","2016-11-01","<p>We are not aware of any public authority being allocated funding specifically for these inquests.</p>","Wyre and Preston North","Mr Ben Wallace",,"2016-11-01T14:09:03.377Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/620039/answer","Biography information for Mr Ben Wallace","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/620039/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/620039/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2016-10-24","Bombings: Birmingham","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, whether any Government departments, public bodies or other organisations have been allocated funds from the public purse for legal representation in connection with the resumed inquests into the murder of 21 people in the Birmingham pub bombings of November 1974.","false","Biography information for Steve McCabe","Birmingham, Selly Oak","Steve McCabe","49945"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/620040","Department for Transport","false","2016-10-27","<p>The invitation list for the round table is yet to be finalised. People from a number of organisations have been asked to keep the time on 17<sup>th</sup> November available. The organisations (other than Government) involved are Abbey Logistics Group, the British International Freight Association, British Ports, the Chartered Institute of Logistics and Transport, the Freight Transport Association, Freightlink Europe, Labyrinth Solutions, the Rail Delivery Group, Rail Freight Group, the Recruitment and Employment Confederation, the Road Haulage Association, Unite the Union, the UK Major Ports Group and the UK Warehousing Association.</p><p> </p>","South Holland and The Deepings","Mr John Hayes",,"2016-10-27T10:57:42.687Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/620040/answer","Biography information for Sir John Hayes","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/620040/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/620040/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2016-10-24","Large Goods Vehicle Drivers","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, which organisations and individuals have been invited to attend the logistics industry round table to discuss driver shortage and future recruitment on 17 November 2016.","false","Biography information for Robert Flello","Stoke-on-Trent South","Robert Flello","49969"
