"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/620058","Women and Equalities","false","2016-11-02","<p>The Government Equalities Office issues from time to time guidance on the Public Sector Equality Duty to Whitehall Departments. This is circulated with a view to enabling them to add any supporting documentation about their own processes before publishing the material on their intranets.</p><p> </p><p>The guidance was last issued in September 2014. The Department will publish that guidance in updated form on GOV.UK in due course.</p><ul><li><p> </p></li></ul>","Gosport","Caroline Dinenage",,"2016-11-02T18:00:27.08Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/620058/answer","Biography information for Caroline Dinenage","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/620058/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/620058/answer",,,,,"31","Women and Equalities","Women and Equalities","2016-10-24","Public Sector: Equality","1","House of Commons","To ask the Minister for Women and Equalities, pursuant to the Answer of 20 October 2016 to Question 48607, on equality impact assessments, if her Department will publish the Public Sector Equality Duty guidance circulated across Whitehall.","false","Biography information for Dawn Butler","Brent Central","Dawn Butler","49845"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/620059","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2016-10-27","<p>Details of Ministerial UK official visits and official meetings with external organisations and individuals are published quarterly and made available on the gov.uk website.</p>","East Hampshire","Damian Hinds",,"2016-10-27T14:06:38.427Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/620059/answer","Biography information for Mr Damian Hinds","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/620059/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/620059/answer",,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2016-10-24","Food Banks","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, (a) how many and (b) which food banks he has visited since taking office.","false","Biography information for Mr David Winnick","Walsall North","Mr David Winnick","49827"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/620060","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2016-10-27","<p>The Department for Work and Pensions does not hold sufficient data on self-employed recipients of in-work benefits to answer this question.</p>","East Hampshire","Damian Hinds",,"2016-10-27T14:21:44.46Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/620060/answer","Biography information for Mr Damian Hinds","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/620060/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/620060/answer",,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2016-10-24","Social Security Benefits: Self-employed","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, how many people who are certified as self-employed in Ashfield constituency are in receipt of in-work benefits.","false","Biography information for Gloria De Piero","Ashfield","Gloria De Piero","49831"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/620061","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2016-11-01","<p>Statutory Sick Pay (SSP) provides a measure of earnings replacement for employees unable to work because of short-term sickness if they satisfy the qualifying conditions, which are not related to specific medical conditions.</p><p>Those who are not entitled to SSP or are still unwell at the end of the maximum payment period (28 weeks) may, provided they satisfy the conditions of entitlement, be entitled to Employment and Support Allowance (ESA).</p><p>As two people with the same condition can be affected in different ways, there is no condition-based entitlement to ESA. The Work Capability Assessment recognises that conditions can vary in their severity and therefore people with the same condition could be placed in the Work Related Activity Group, the Support Group or found fit for work.</p>","Portsmouth North","Penny Mordaunt",,"2016-11-01T16:58:44.157Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/620061/answer","Biography information for Penny Mordaunt","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/620061/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/620061/answer",,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2016-10-24","Sick Pay and Social Security Benefits: Endometriosis","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, what assessment his Department has made of the adequacy of access to sick pay and state benefits for women who suffer from severe endometriosis.","false","Biography information for Vicky Foxcroft","Lewisham, Deptford","Vicky Foxcroft","49870"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/620062","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2016-11-01","<p>The government is aware that the exceptions to the policy to limit the child element in Universal Credit and the individual element in Child Tax Credit to a maximum of two children are sensitive. We contacted a number of organisations in August 2015 and met with several of those organisations in early 2016 to discuss the exceptions. Officials have also discussed this issue between government departments and at wider DWP and HMRC stakeholder meetings.</p><p>The government launched a consultation on 21 October 2016 to seek evidence and invite views from stakeholders to inform the design of the exceptions and their implementation. All Ministers with an interest are consulted as part of the clearance process for any Government consultation. The consultation document is published online here: https://www.gov.uk/government/consultations/universal-credit-and-child-tax-credit-exceptions-to-the-2-child-limit</p><p>The consultation closes on 27 November 2016.</p>","East Hampshire","Damian Hinds","50087","2016-11-01T12:02:30.58Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/620062/answer","Biography information for Mr Damian Hinds","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/620062/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/620062/answer",,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2016-10-24","Welfare Tax Credits","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, with which organisations and on which dates his Department has discussed plans to protect survivors of rape and sexual abuse whose third child was born as a result of rape and would wish to claim tax credits in the last year.","false","Biography information for Alison Thewliss","Glasgow Central","Alison Thewliss","50010"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/620063","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2016-11-01","<p>The 2012 scheme includes an Annual Review of the Non-Resident Parent’s income. If their income is being determined on the basis of Current Income, they are legally required to report any increases of 25% of more in their income level. If they do not, a provision exists for the CMS to backdate a new calculation decision to the point in the year that the change occurred.</p><p>In addition, a Non-Resident Parent may choose to report a change of circumstance, including changes to their income, to the Child Maintenance Service, which will consider making a new decision about the amount of maintenance due reflecting those changes. Once a decision in relation to the reported change has been made, that decision is notified to both clients.</p><p>If either parent believes the decision is wrong, they may request the Child Maintenance Service revisit the decision (a Mandatory Reconsideration), after which they may appeal to an independent First-tier Tribunal.</p><p> </p>","Romsey and Southampton North","Caroline Nokes",,"2016-11-01T12:55:54.803Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/620063/answer","Biography information for Caroline Nokes","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/620063/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/620063/answer",,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2016-10-24","Children: Maintenance","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, what arrangements he has put in place to assess the effectiveness of the provisions in the 2012 Scheme for varying child support payments following changes in the income of the paying parent.","false","Biography information for Kirsten Oswald","East Renfrewshire","Kirsten  Oswald","49935"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/620064","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2016-11-01","<p>We are grateful for this report focusing on care leavers from the Children’s Society, and for their recommendations, which we will consider as part of our continuous review of sanctions policy to ensure the process functions effectively and fairly. I can assure you that where we identify an issue, we act to put it right.</p><p>For care leavers, as with other claimants, the sanctions process encourages them to prepare for or find work, by meeting their agreed commitments based on their individual circumstances and capabilities, as set out in their Claimant Commitment. This includes both mandatory and voluntary actions care leavers have agreed to undertake. The consequences and implications of not meeting any agreed requirement are clearly set out and explained to them.</p><p>A decision to apply a sanction is not taken lightly, and claimants are given the opportunity to provide a good reason for not complying before the decision is made.</p><p>Our primary goal is to help care leavers get into work wherever possible and they receive tailored, locally-appropriate employment support at the earliest opportunity to achieve this.</p><p>Care leavers, like all claimants, take ownership of planning how they will meet their requirements and ultimately secure employment. They will be supported by their Work Coach who will assist them in meeting their requirements through providing encouragement and direction, using a range of communication methods. Work Coaches support all claimants who require additional support to ensure that they fully understand what they have been asked to do to enable them to access DWP benefits and use our services.</p>","East Hampshire","Damian Hinds",,"2016-11-01T16:36:18.647Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/620064/answer","Biography information for Mr Damian Hinds","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/620064/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/620064/answer",,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2016-10-24","Care Leavers","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, with reference to page 19 of the Children's Society Report entitled the cost of being care free: the impact of poor financial education and removal of support on care leavers, published in 2016, what plans he has to better protect care leavers.","false","Biography information for Helen Hayes","Dulwich and West Norwood","Helen Hayes","50036"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/620065","Department for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","false","2016-11-01","<p>The Coal Mining Subsidence Act 1991 and the Coal Industry Act 1994 set out the duties on the Coal Authority in relation to coal mining subsidence and includes provisions for purchase of properties and home loss payments. Principles relating to compensation reflect similar principles referred to in other codes of practice relating to compulsory purchase procedures instigated by other public bodies. However, the Coal Authority has no compulsory purchase rights relating to subsidence. There are, however, differences in the minimum and maximum degree of compensation paid.</p>","Hereford and South Herefordshire","Jesse Norman",,"2016-11-01T16:37:47.637Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/620065/answer","Biography information for Jesse Norman","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/620065/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/620065/answer",,,,,"201","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","2016-10-24","Mining: Subsidence","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy, whether it is his Department's policy that compensation for subsidence damage under the Coal Mining Subsidence Act 1991 is in line with the Code of Practice which was based upon the Land Compensation Act 1973.","false","Biography information for Sir Alan Campbell","Tynemouth","Mr Alan Campbell","50031"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/620066","Department for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","false","2016-10-31","<p>My rt. hon. Friend the Secretary of State has no plans to review the powers under the Coal Mining Subsidence Act 1991.</p>","Hereford and South Herefordshire","Jesse Norman",,"2016-10-31T14:36:39.817Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/620066/answer","Biography information for Jesse Norman","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/620066/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/620066/answer",,,,,"201","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","2016-10-24","Mining: Subsidence","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy, what plans he has to amend the Coal Mining Subsidence Act 1991 to allow the Coal Authority to take into account blight when making compensation payments.","false","Biography information for Sir Alan Campbell","Tynemouth","Mr Alan Campbell","50032"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/620067","Department for Communities and Local Government","false","2016-11-01","<p>The Home Loss Payments (Prescribed Amounts) (England) Regulations 2015 have been replaced by the 2016 Regulations SI 2016 No. 789. These regulations apply where the displacement is on or after 1<sup>st</sup> October 2016.</p><p>The minimum payment is £5,800 and the maximum payment is £58,000 for qualifying owner occupiers.</p><p>A flat rate payment of £5,800 is made for qualifying tenants.</p>","Croydon Central","Gavin Barwell",,"2016-11-01T15:35:38.52Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/620067/answer","Biography information for Lord Barwell","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/620067/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/620067/answer",,,,,"7","Communities and Local Government","Communities and Local Government","2016-10-24","Compulsory Purchase: Compensation","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Communities and Local Government, what the (a) minimum and (b) maximum amount payable is under the Home Loss Payments (Prescribed Amounts) (England) Regulations 2015.","false","Biography information for Sir Alan Campbell","Tynemouth","Mr Alan Campbell","50033"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/620068","Department for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","false","2016-10-31","<p>The Coal Authority has no compulsory purchase powers in relation to subsidence and as such has not purchased any properties on that basis in the last five years.</p>","Hereford and South Herefordshire","Jesse Norman",,"2016-10-31T14:36:52.3Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/620068/answer","Biography information for Jesse Norman","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/620068/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/620068/answer",,,,,"201","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","2016-10-24","Mining: Subsidence","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy, how many properties affected by subsidence have been compulsorily purchased by the Coal Authority in each of the last five years.","false","Biography information for Sir Alan Campbell","Tynemouth","Mr Alan Campbell","50034"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/620069","Department for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","false","2016-11-01","<p>The independent review on Tidal Lagoons in the UK, headed by Charles Hendry will report towards the end of the year and will consider, among other things, whether and in what circumstances tidal lagoons could play a cost effective role in the energy mix.</p>","Ruislip, Northwood and Pinner","Mr Nick Hurd","50096","2016-11-01T14:19:24.047Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/620069/answer","Biography information for Mr Nick Hurd","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/620069/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/620069/answer",,,,,"201","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","2016-10-24","Tidal Power: Swansea Bay","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy, whether the potential economic benefits of tidal power lagoons will be considered in the development of the Government's new Industrial Strategy.","false","Biography information for Oliver Colvile","Plymouth, Sutton and Devonport","Oliver Colvile","50035"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/620070","Department for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","false","2016-10-27","<p>A total of 41 customers were interviewed as part of the evaluation of the Energy Rebate scheme.</p><p> </p><p>These customers were drawn from four representative sample groups of interest.</p><p> </p><p>The findings of the research can be found here: <a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/uploads/system/uploads/attachment_data/file/220145/energy-rebate-scheme-evaluation.pdf" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/government/uploads/system/uploads/attachment_data/file/220145/energy-rebate-scheme-evaluation.pdf</a></p><p> </p>","Hereford and South Herefordshire","Jesse Norman",,"2016-10-27T16:51:16.14Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/620070/answer","Biography information for Jesse Norman","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/620070/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/620070/answer",,,,,"201","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","2016-10-24","Warm Home Discount Scheme","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy, pursuant to the Answer of 24 October 2016 to Question 48717, how many customers were interviewed in the small-scale qualitative evaluation of the Warm Home Discount scheme.","false","Biography information for Chi Onwurah","Newcastle upon Tyne Central","Chi Onwurah","50018"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/620071","Department for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","false","2016-10-27","<p>The scheme has formal arrangements in place for individuals wishing to opt-out from the scheme.</p><p> </p><p>All Pension Credit Guarantee Credit recipients are first sent a letter with information about the scheme. Only these recipients automatically receive the Warm Home Discount rebate. Those who do not want their data shared with their energy supplier, can write to Department Work for Pensions stating their wish to opt-out from the scheme.</p>","Hereford and South Herefordshire","Jesse Norman",,"2016-10-27T16:49:52.617Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/620071/answer","Biography information for Jesse Norman","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/620071/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/620071/answer",,,,,"201","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","2016-10-24","Warm Home Discount Scheme","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy, pursuant to the Answer of 21 October 2016 to Question 49308, on the Warm Home Discount Scheme, how a person opts out of that scheme.","false","Biography information for Chi Onwurah","Newcastle upon Tyne Central","Chi Onwurah","49884"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/620072","Department for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","false","2016-11-01","<p>I am in close contact with Commissioner Moedas, who has responsibility for EU science, research and innovation and we have both publicly emphasised the importance of continuing to work together to produce high quality research. In addition, the European Commission has made it clear that while the UK remains a member of the EU, proposals from, or including, UK applicants must be treated in the same way as applications from other Member States. The Department remains vigilant and open to evidence of problems in this area. Specific instances of these problems can be fed back to the email address <a href="mailto:research@beis.gov.uk" target="_blank">research@beis.gov.uk</a>.</p>","Orpington","Joseph Johnson",,"2016-11-01T16:04:06.77Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/620072/answer","Biography information for Joseph  Johnson","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/620072/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/620072/answer",,,,,"201","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","2016-10-24","Research: EU Grants and Loans","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy, what discussions he has had with EU Science Commissioner Carlos Moedas on potential discrimination against UK academics who bid for EU funding.","false","Biography information for Diana Johnson","Kingston upon Hull North","Diana Johnson","49885"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/620073","Department for Transport","false","2016-11-01","<p>The Government does not believe that the Ports Services Regulation is necessary or desirable.</p><p>However, until we leave, EU law will continue to apply to the UK. The Department will continue to work alongside the Department for Exiting the European Union, which has the responsibility for leading the negotiations to leave the EU, and for the future relationship between the UK and EU.</p><p> </p>","South Holland and The Deepings","Mr John Hayes",,"2016-11-01T11:36:36.293Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/620073/answer","Biography information for Sir John Hayes","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/620073/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/620073/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2016-10-24","Ports: EU Law","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, if he will make it his policy that the EU Port Services Regulation is not replaced in UK law after the UK leaves the EU.","false","Biography information for Grant Shapps","Welwyn Hatfield","Grant Shapps","49890"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/620074","Department for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","false","2016-10-28","<p>Renewables subsidies are estimated to account for around 6% of an average household dual fuel bill of £1,029 in 2016.*</p><p> </p><p>* Source: National Audit Office analysis of Department of Energy &amp; Climate Change data, July 2016. Figures in real 2011/12 prices.</p>","Hereford and South Herefordshire","Jesse Norman",,"2016-10-28T13:44:05.177Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/620074/answer","Biography information for Jesse Norman","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/620074/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/620074/answer",,,,,"201","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","2016-10-24","Electricity: Prices","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy, if he will make an assessment of the effect of the renewable subsidies programme on household electricity bills.","false","Biography information for Grant Shapps","Welwyn Hatfield","Grant Shapps","49891"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/620076","Department for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","false","2016-11-01","<p>The Government is committed to maintain and enhance the strength of our research base. This is why we have protected the science resource budget in real terms from its 2015/16 level of £4.7 billion for the rest of the parliament, as well as committing to invest in new scientific infrastructure on a record scale – £6.9 billion over the period 2015-2021 – including £65 million in the North East in 2014/15.</p><p>The Treasury decision to underwrite the grants of competitively bid for EU research funding will give British participants and their EU partners the assurance and certainty needed to plan ahead for projects that can run over many years. We will ensure that the UK, including Yorkshire and the Humber, continues to be a world leader in international research and innovation.</p>","Orpington","Joseph Johnson",,"2016-11-01T16:03:07.717Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/620076/answer","Biography information for Joseph  Johnson","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/620076/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/620076/answer",,,,,"201","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","2016-10-24","Universities: Yorkshire and the Humber","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy, what assessment he has made of the potential effect of the UK leaving the EU on research funding across all disciplines in universities in Yorkshire and the Humber.","false","Biography information for Craig Whittaker","Calder Valley","Craig Whittaker","49916"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/620077","Department for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","false","2016-10-27","<p>The Department for Culture, Media &amp; Sport (DCMS) is responsible for the Government’s policy on nuisance telephone calls. The hon. Member’s letter of 20 September 2016 has been passed to DCMS and that Department will reply directly to the hon Member.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p>","Stourbridge","Margot James",,"2016-10-27T13:04:42.17Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/620077/answer","Biography information for Margot James","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/620077/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/620077/answer",,,,,"201","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","2016-10-24","Members: Correspondence","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy, when his Department plans to reply to the letter from the hon. Member for Walsall North of 20 September 2016 on behalf of a constituent relating to nuisance telephone calls.","false","Biography information for Mr David Winnick","Walsall North","Mr David Winnick","49828"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/620078","Department for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","false","2016-10-27","<p>Since the beginning of this Parliament, no discussions have taken place between the Department and the senior management team at the Royal Bank of Scotland (RBS) about the bank’s Global Restructuring Group. This matter is currently being investigated by the Financial Conduct Authority (FCA).</p>","Stourbridge","Margot James",,"2016-10-27T14:15:58.89Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/620078/answer","Biography information for Margot James","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/620078/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/620078/answer",,,,,"201","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","2016-10-24","Global Restructuring Group","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy, what discussions his Department has had with the senior management team at the Royal Bank of Scotland on that Bank's global restructuring group and that group's treatment of small businesses during the financial crisis.","false","Biography information for Greg Mulholland","Leeds North West","Greg Mulholland","49846"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/620079","Department for International Trade","false","2016-10-31","<p>The Prime Minister has been clear that we are not going to provide a running commentary on our approach to negotiations. We recognise the need for a smooth transition as the UK leaves the EU which minimises disruption to our trading relationships. The Government is discussing our future trade relationship with a range of countries, including those in the European Free Trade Association.</p><p> </p>","Chelsea and Fulham","Greg Hands",,"2016-10-31T15:07:11.21Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/620079/answer","Biography information for Greg Hands","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/620079/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/620079/answer",,,,,"202","International Trade","International Trade","2016-10-24","European Free Trade Association","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for International Trade, what assessment he has made of the possibility of the UK rejoining the European Free Trade Association.","false","Biography information for Charlotte Leslie","Bristol North West","Charlotte Leslie","50013"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/620080","Department for Exiting the European Union","false","2016-10-27","<p>The UK’s economy is unique, and the relationship we secure with the EU has to reflect that.</p><p>Supported by departments across government, DExEU is analysing the entire UK economy to understand the key factors for business and the labour force that will affect our negotiations with the EU. We have structured this analysis by looking in detail at over 50 sectors and cross-cutting regulatory issues. This will ensure that we can take full account of the opportunities and issues which arise for the economy from EU exit and get the best deal for the UK.</p><p> </p>","Clwyd West","Mr David Jones",,"2016-10-27T13:13:02.627Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/620080/answer","Biography information for Mr David Jones","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/620080/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/620080/answer",,,,,"203","Exiting the European Union","Exiting the European Union","2016-10-24","Brexit","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Exiting the European Union, pursuant to his oral contribution of 12 October 2016, Official Report, column 331, what his policy is on what should be included in the British option he described; and if he will make a statement.","false","Biography information for Mr Jim Cunningham","Coventry South","Mr Jim Cunningham","49977"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/620081","Department for Exiting the European Union","false","2016-10-27","<p>The Government will bring forward legislation in the next session that, when enacted, will repeal the European Communities Act 1972 on the day we leave the EU. This ‘Great Repeal Bill’ will end the authority of EU law and return power to the UK.</p><p>The Bill will transpose current EU law into domestic law, while allowing for amendments to take account of the future negotiated UK-EU relationship. Without pre-judging this future relationship or future decisions Parliament may make, it will give consumers, workers and businesses as much certainty as possible by maintaining law wherever practicable and desirable.</p><p>The Government will set out the content of the Bill and its implications in due course.</p>","Clwyd West","Mr David Jones",,"2016-10-27T13:10:06.767Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/620081/answer","Biography information for Mr David Jones","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/620081/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/620081/answer",,,,,"203","Exiting the European Union","Exiting the European Union","2016-10-24","EU Law","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Exiting the European Union, what legislation his Department plans to repeal using the Great Repeal Bill; and if he will make a statement.","false","Biography information for Mr Jim Cunningham","Coventry South","Mr Jim Cunningham","49908"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/620082","HM Treasury","false","2016-11-01","<p>There are a whole range of issues and elements to our relationship with the European Union that will need to be addressed as we leave.</p><p> </p><p>These issues affect both sides, the UK and the EU. The government will not be giving a running commentary on the details.</p><p> </p>","South West Hertfordshire","Mr David Gauke",,"2016-11-01T12:38:13.597Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/620082/answer","Biography information for Mr David Gauke","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/620082/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/620082/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2016-10-24","Brexit","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, what estimate he has made of the earliest date by which the UK will be able to discharge the liabilities entered into during its time as an EU member state when exiting from the EU.","false","Biography information for Matthew Pennycook","Greenwich and Woolwich","Matthew Pennycook","49878"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/620830","Attorney General","false","2016-10-27","<p>The number of sentences considered by my office has increased by over 108% since 2010 from 342 to 713 requests in 2015.</p><p> </p><p>Of those, 136 were referred by my office to the Court of Appeal as potentially unduly lenient, with the Court agreeing to increase the original sentence for 102 offenders.</p>","South Swindon","Robert Buckland",,"2016-10-27T16:24:18.1Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/620830/answer","Biography information for Robert Buckland","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/620830/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/620830/answer",,,,,"88","Attorney General","Attorney General","2016-10-24","Sentencing","1","House of Commons","To ask the Attorney General, what assessment he has made of the effectiveness of the unduly lenient sentence scheme.","false","Biography information for Karl McCartney","Lincoln","Karl McCartney","906822"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/621043","Women and Equalities","false","2016-10-27","<p>We value diversity but want the best people in the classroom, as evidence shows that quality of teaching is the single most important factor in determining how well pupils achieve.</p><p>Recent figures show that from 2011/12 to 2015/16, the number of full-time equivalent male teachers increased from 115,000 to nearly 120,000. Last year, 26 per cent of teachers in state schools were male.</p>","Gosport","Caroline Dinenage",,"2016-10-27T15:18:54.443Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/621043/answer","Biography information for Caroline Dinenage","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/621043/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/621043/answer",,,,,"31","Women and Equalities","Women and Equalities","2016-10-24","Teachers: Males","1","House of Commons","To ask the Minister for Women and Equalities, what steps the Government is taking to increase the number of male teachers.","false","Biography information for Karl McCartney","Lincoln","Karl McCartney","906861"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/622069","Attorney General","false","2016-10-27","<p>The European Arrest Warrant (EAW) provides a basis for a swift and cost-efficient extradition process between EU Member States implementing the principle of ‘mutual recognition’ of judicial decisions. The UK continues to work closely with Member States to execute EAW following the referendum.</p>","South Swindon","Robert Buckland",,"2016-10-27T16:25:11.623Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/622069/answer","Biography information for Robert Buckland","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/622069/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/622069/answer",,,,,"88","Attorney General","Attorney General","2016-10-24","European Arrest Warrants","1","House of Commons","To ask the Attorney General, what assessment he has made of the effectiveness of the use of the European Arrest Warrant.","false","Biography information for David Hanson","Delyn","Mr David Hanson","906829"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/622314","Attorney General","false","2016-10-27","<p>We are committed to tackling hate crime in any form. The cross Government Hate Crime Action Plan, published in July 2016, focuses on reducing hate crime, increasing reporting and ensuring that all criminal justice partners and key stakeholders deliver the appropriate outcomes for victims.</p>","South Swindon","Robert Buckland",,"2016-10-27T16:25:32.12Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/622314/answer","Biography information for Robert Buckland","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/622314/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/622314/answer",,,,,"88","Attorney General","Attorney General","2016-10-24","Hate Crime: Prosecutions","1","House of Commons","To ask the Attorney General, what steps the Government is taking to increase the number of prosecutions for hate crime.","false","Biography information for Mr Marcus Fysh","Yeovil","Marcus Fysh","906831"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/622315","Attorney General","false","2016-10-27","<p>We are committed to tackling hate crime in any form. The cross Government Hate Crime Action Plan, published in July 2016, focuses on reducing hate crime, increasing reporting and ensuring that all criminal justice partners and key stakeholders deliver the appropriate outcomes for victims.</p>","South Swindon","Robert Buckland",,"2016-10-27T16:24:30.87Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/622315/answer","Biography information for Robert Buckland","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/622315/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/622315/answer",,,,,"88","Attorney General","Attorney General","2016-10-24","Hate Crime: Prosecutions","1","House of Commons","To ask the Attorney General, what recent steps the Crown Prosecution Service has taken to set out its approach to prosecuting hate crime.","false","Biography information for Paul Blomfield","Sheffield Central","Paul Blomfield","906832"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/622316","Attorney General","false","2016-10-27","<p>Over the past two years the Serious Fraud Office has secured:</p><ul><li>the first contested convictions for rate rigging,</li><li>its first contested conviction of a corporate for offences involving bribery of foreign officials,</li><li>the first two Deferred Prosecution Agreements in the UK, and</li><li>the first conviction of a corporate for an offence under s7 of the Bribery Act.</li></ul>","South Swindon","Robert Buckland",,"2016-10-27T16:25:24.877Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/622316/answer","Biography information for Robert Buckland","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/622316/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/622316/answer",,,,,"88","Attorney General","Attorney General","2016-10-24","Fraud: Crime Prevention","1","House of Commons","To ask the Attorney General, what recent steps the Serious Fraud Office has taken to prevent serious fraud and other economic crimes.","false","Biography information for Chris Elmore","Ogmore","Chris Elmore","906830"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/622317","Women and Equalities","false","2016-10-27","<p>The UK has some of the strongest equality legislation and policies in the world. This will continue to be the case after we leave the EU. The Government Equalities Office will continue to follow an ambitious programme of work to ensure that everyone has a fair chance and that no one is discriminated against because of their background.</p>","Gosport","Caroline Dinenage",,"2016-10-27T15:09:34.957Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/622317/answer","Biography information for Caroline Dinenage","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/622317/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/622317/answer",,,,,"31","Women and Equalities","Women and Equalities","2016-10-24","Equality","1","House of Commons","To ask the Minister for Women and Equalities, what assessment she has made of the potential implications of the UK leaving the EU for the Government's policies on equality.","false","Biography information for Patrick Grady","Glasgow North","Patrick Grady","906863"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/622318","Women and Equalities","false","2016-10-27","<p>Abusive or threatening behaviour – whoever the target - is totally unacceptable. As set out in the Violence Against Women and Girls prevention strategy, my department, with the Home Office, has established a cross-government working group to develop proactive responses to online misogyny. We have also provided new funding for the Revenge Porn Helpline.</p>","Gosport","Caroline Dinenage",,"2016-10-27T15:09:04.01Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/622318/answer","Biography information for Caroline Dinenage","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/622318/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/622318/answer",,,,,"31","Women and Equalities","Women and Equalities","2016-10-24","Hate Crime: Females","1","House of Commons","To ask the Minister for Women and Equalities, what steps the Government is taking to tackle the rise in online misogyny.","false","Biography information for Alex Chalk","Cheltenham","Alex Chalk","906862"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/622319","Women and Equalities","false","2016-10-27","<p>We have more women on boards than ever before and no all-male boards in the FTSE 100. We have established the new, independent Hampton-Alexander Review which will have a particular focus on improving gender representation in the all-important executive layer of the FTSE companies.</p><p>I fully endorse the business-led target of 33% women on FTSE 350 boards by 2020 and would like to go further.</p>","Gosport","Caroline Dinenage",,"2016-10-27T15:18:18.363Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/622319/answer","Biography information for Caroline Dinenage","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/622319/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/622319/answer",,,,,"31","Women and Equalities","Women and Equalities","2016-10-24","Females: Directors","1","House of Commons","To ask the Minister for Women and Equalities, what steps the Government is taking to increase the number of women on boards and at senior executive levels of FTSE companies.","false","Biography information for Nigel Huddleston","Mid Worcestershire","Nigel Huddleston","906865"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/622320","Women and Equalities","false","2016-10-27","<p>The Government wants to ensure that all schools are safe, inclusive environments where pupils are able to learn and fulfil their potential.</p><p>We know that pupils who are, or perceived to be, LGBT are disproportionately affected by bullying. This bullying can have a devastating effect on them, their education and their mental health.</p><p>This is why we recently announced a three year, £2.8 million, programme to prevent and address homophobic, biphobic and transphobic bullying in schools.</p>","Gosport","Caroline Dinenage",,"2016-10-27T15:14:48.897Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/622320/answer","Biography information for Caroline Dinenage","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/622320/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/622320/answer",,,,,"31","Women and Equalities","Women and Equalities","2016-10-24","Bullying: Schools","1","House of Commons","To ask the Minister for Women and Equalities, what steps the Government is taking to (a) tackle homophobic, biphobic and transphobic bullying in schools and (b) establish inclusive schools.","false","Biography information for Stuart Andrew","Pudsey","Stuart Andrew","906864"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/622321","Women and Equalities","false","2016-10-28","<p>The Department of Health has asked the <a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Advisory_Committee_on_the_Safety_of_Blood,_Tissues_and_Organs" target="_blank">Advisory Committee on the Safety of Blood, Tissues and Organs</a> to review the donor selection criteria for blood donation including those that relate to men who have sex with men.</p><p> </p><p>The review is holding its third meeting this year in November and is on schedule to report in mid-2017.</p>","Gosport","Caroline Dinenage",,"2016-10-28T14:00:23.033Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/622321/answer","Biography information for Caroline Dinenage","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/622321/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/622321/answer",,,,,"31","Women and Equalities","Women and Equalities","2016-10-24","Blood: Donors","1","House of Commons","To ask the Minister for Women and Equalities, what progress has been made on changing restrictions on gay men being permitted to donate blood; and if she will make a statement.","false","Biography information for Michael Fabricant","Lichfield","Michael Fabricant","906866"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/607500","Cabinet Office","false","2016-10-26","<p>The 2016 Budget announced that government would develop options for an authoritative address register that is open and freely available. It is critical that we make wider use of more precise address data and ensure it is frequently updated to unlock opportunities for innovation.</p><p>Since the Budget, officials from across government have been exploring a range of potential options for the creation of an Open Address Register and I will look to update the House once this work has been concluded.</p>","Kingswood","Chris Skidmore",,"2016-10-26T11:25:02.673Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/607500/answer","Biography information for Chris Skidmore","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/607500/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/607500/answer",,,,,"53","Cabinet Office","Cabinet Office","2016-10-21","Databases","1","House of Commons","To ask the Minister for the Cabinet Office, what recent progress his Department has made on its work on an open address register.","false","Biography information for Chi Onwurah","Newcastle upon Tyne Central","Chi Onwurah","49758"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/607501","Cabinet Office","false","2016-10-26","<p>Open registers will provide significant value across the public sector and the wider economy by transforming how government uses data to drive benefits to citizens, focusing on accuracy, transparency and accessibility of data. Open registers will stimulate and support a wide marketplace of open data products and services, built on high-quality open government data.</p><p>Similar programmes of work in Australia and Denmark have driven significant social and economic benefits; the development of an open address register in Denmark has seen a return on investment in excess of 3000%. We expect that the development of open registers will aid our international competitiveness and help grow our digital economy.</p><p>The Government Digital Service has already delivered a country register with the FCO, with a complementary Territory register also in development. We have just published a Local Authority England register with DCLG. There is a pipeline of additional registers being created that have been prioritised after discussion with government departments and based on the most pressing user need.</p>","Kingswood","Chris Skidmore",,"2016-10-26T11:22:46.61Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/607501/answer","Biography information for Chris Skidmore","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/607501/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/607501/answer",,,,,"53","Cabinet Office","Cabinet Office","2016-10-21","Databases","1","House of Commons","To ask the Minister for the Cabinet Office, what recent estimate his Department has made of the social and economic value to the economy of the open registers being built by the government data programme.","false","Biography information for Chi Onwurah","Newcastle upon Tyne Central","Chi Onwurah","49759"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/607502","HM Treasury","false","2016-10-26","<p>The Government has recently consulted on proposals to limit the range of benefits in kind, such as company cars, that attract income tax and National Insurance Contributions advantages when they are provided as part of salary sacrifice arrangements. Responses have been received from a wide range of interested parties and the Government’s response will be published in due course.</p><p> </p><p>The Government is committed to encouraging company car drivers to take-up the driving of ultra-low emissions vehicles. A separate consultation published on 10 August sets out proposals to incentivise the take up of low and ultra-low emissions company cars.</p><p> </p>","Battersea","Jane Ellison","49809 ; 49810 ; 49811","2016-10-26T15:13:59.31Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/607502/answer","Biography information for Jane Ellison","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/607502/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/607502/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2016-10-21","Company Cars: Public Sector","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, what assessment he has made of the value of salary sacrifice company cars to employers in the public sector for (a) recruiting and (b) retaining for staff.","false","Biography information for Mary Glindon","North Tyneside","Mary Glindon","49782"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/607503","HM Treasury","false","2016-10-26","<p>The Government has recently consulted on proposals to limit the range of benefits in kind, such as company cars, that attract income tax and National Insurance Contributions advantages when they are provided as part of salary sacrifice arrangements. Responses have been received from a wide range of interested parties and the Government’s response will be published in due course.</p><p> </p><p>The Government is committed to encouraging company car drivers to take-up the driving of ultra-low emissions vehicles. A separate consultation published on 10 August sets out proposals to incentivise the take up of low and ultra-low emissions company cars.</p><p> </p>","Battersea","Jane Ellison","49782 ; 49810 ; 49811","2016-10-26T15:13:59.403Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/607503/answer","Biography information for Jane Ellison","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/607503/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/607503/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2016-10-21","Taxation: Company Cars","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, what recent assessment he has made of the effectiveness of taxation rules applied to company cars on incentivising the take-up of low and ultra-low emission vehicles.","false","Biography information for Mary Glindon","North Tyneside","Mary Glindon","49809"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/607504","HM Treasury","false","2016-10-26","<p>The Government has recently consulted on proposals to limit the range of benefits in kind, such as company cars, that attract income tax and National Insurance Contributions advantages when they are provided as part of salary sacrifice arrangements. Responses have been received from a wide range of interested parties and the Government’s response will be published in due course.</p><p> </p><p>The Government is committed to encouraging company car drivers to take-up the driving of ultra-low emissions vehicles. A separate consultation published on 10 August sets out proposals to incentivise the take up of low and ultra-low emissions company cars.</p><p> </p>","Battersea","Jane Ellison","49782 ; 49809 ; 49811","2016-10-26T15:13:59.467Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/607504/answer","Biography information for Jane Ellison","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/607504/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/607504/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2016-10-21","Taxation: Company Cars","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, what assessment he has made of the potential effect on basic rate taxpayers who drive low and ultra-low emission company cars of proposals contained in the HM Revenue and Customs' consultation on salary sacrifice for the provision of benefits in kind.","false","Biography information for Mary Glindon","North Tyneside","Mary Glindon","49810"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/607505","HM Treasury","false","2016-10-26","<p>The Government has recently consulted on proposals to limit the range of benefits in kind, such as company cars, that attract income tax and National Insurance Contributions advantages when they are provided as part of salary sacrifice arrangements. Responses have been received from a wide range of interested parties and the Government’s response will be published in due course.</p><p> </p><p>The Government is committed to encouraging company car drivers to take-up the driving of ultra-low emissions vehicles. A separate consultation published on 10 August sets out proposals to incentivise the take up of low and ultra-low emissions company cars.</p><p> </p>","Battersea","Jane Ellison","49782 ; 49809 ; 49810","2016-10-26T15:13:59.527Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/607505/answer","Biography information for Jane Ellison","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/607505/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/607505/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2016-10-21","Taxation: Company Cars","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, what estimate he has made of the number of basic rate taxpaying company car drivers who will potentially pay more tax as a result of proposals in the HM Revenue and Customs' consultation on salary sacrifice for the provision of benefits in kind.","false","Biography information for Mary Glindon","North Tyneside","Mary Glindon","49811"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/607506","Department for Education","false","2016-10-31","<p>The Department for Education does not collect this information. If any children are awaiting placement with foster carers, that information will be kept at local authority level. As at March 2015 there were 73,845 approved foster carers in England.</p>","Crewe and Nantwich","Edward Timpson",,"2016-10-31T16:48:42.623Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/607506/answer","Biography information for Edward Timpson","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/607506/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/607506/answer",,,,,"60","Education","Education","2016-10-21","Foster Care","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Education, how many children in local authority care are awaiting placement with foster parents.","false","Biography information for David T. C. Davies","Monmouth","David T. C. Davies","49745"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/607507","Department for Communities and Local Government","false","2016-10-26","<p>One person without a home is one too many. This is why on Monday 24 October the Government announced its support for Mr Blackman’s Homelessness Reduction Bill.</p><p>The Bill will significantly reform England’s homelessness legislation, ensuring that more people get the help they need to prevent a homelessness crisis in the first place.</p><p>The Government will fund any additional costs in line with the longstanding 'new burdens' arrangements.</p>","Nuneaton","Mr Marcus Jones",,"2016-10-26T14:19:48.653Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/607507/answer","Biography information for Mr Marcus Jones","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/607507/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/607507/answer",,,,,"7","Communities and Local Government","Communities and Local Government","2016-10-21","Homelessness Reduction Bill","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Communities and Local Government, with reference to the oral evidence of the Minister of State for Local Government to the Communities and Local Government Committee on 14 September 2016, at Questions 84 to 87, HC635, whether he plans to publish an estimated cost of the draft Homelessness Reduction Bill before its Second Reading.","false","Biography information for John Healey","Wentworth and Dearne","John Healey","49757"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/607508","Department for Communities and Local Government","false","2016-10-26","<p>The Government has recently launched the new Help to Buy: Shared Ownership scheme which enables people to purchase an initial 25% to 75% of a new home and pay rent on the remainder with the option to purchase more later. It is open to those with a household income below £80,000 in England or £90,000 in London. The Government has no plans to combine this with Help to Buy: Equity Loan.</p>","Croydon Central","Gavin Barwell",,"2016-10-26T14:23:19.037Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/607508/answer","Biography information for Lord Barwell","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/607508/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/607508/answer",,,,,"7","Communities and Local Government","Communities and Local Government","2016-10-21","Help to Buy Scheme: Shared Ownership","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Communities and Local Government, if he will extend the Help to Buy scheme to shared ownership housing association tenants.","false","Biography information for Mr Peter Bone","Wellingborough","Mr Peter Bone","49761"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/607509","Department for Culture, Media and Sport","false","2016-10-28","<p>We have ongoing, detailed discussions with the Games industry and others on all matters, including the UK leaving the EU. The Games industry is represented on the Creative Industries Council, which met on the 27th October 2016.</p>","West Suffolk","Matt Hancock",,"2016-10-28T10:45:42.23Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/607509/answer","Biography information for Matt Hancock","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/607509/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/607509/answer",,,,,"10","Culture, Media and Sport","Culture, Media and Sport","2016-10-21","Video Games","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Culture, Media and Sport, what discussions she has had with the games industry on the potential effects on that industry of the UK leaving the EU.","false","Biography information for Tom Watson","West Bromwich East","Tom Watson","49776"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/607510","Ministry of Defence","false","2016-10-31","<p>Hydroplane bolts are externally located equipment, whereas the BR Standard referred to, albeit superseded, sets standards for internal equipment. The Department is satisfied that appropriate standards are met for this equipment in accordance with our existing guidance.</p>","West Worcestershire","Harriett Baldwin",,"2016-10-31T16:57:45.787Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/607510/answer","Biography information for Harriett Baldwin","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/607510/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/607510/answer",,,,,"11","Defence","Defence","2016-10-21","Submarines: Safety","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Defence, whether it is his Department's policy that all submarines being constructed for the Royal Navy meet shock standard BR3021 as a minimum in respect of hydroplane bolts.","false","Biography information for Jeremy Lefroy","Stafford","Jeremy Lefroy","49743"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/607511","Ministry of Defence","false","2016-10-27","<p>From 1 October 2015 to 25 October 2016 the UK conducted 1,991 combat missions over Iraq. Broken down by month these are:</p><p> </p><table><tbody><tr><td><p> </p></td><td><p>Typhoon FGR4</p></td><td><p>Tornado GR4</p></td><td><p>Reaper MQ9</p></td></tr><tr><td><p><strong>2015</strong></p></td><td><p> </p></td><td><p> </p></td><td><p> </p></td></tr><tr><td><p>October</p></td><td><p>0</p></td><td><p>45</p></td><td><p>61</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>November</p></td><td><p>0</p></td><td><p>52</p></td><td><p>62</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>December</p></td><td><p>47</p></td><td><p>72</p></td><td><p>56</p></td></tr><tr><td><p><strong>2016</strong></p></td><td><p> </p></td><td><p> </p></td><td><p> </p></td></tr><tr><td><p>January</p></td><td><p>48</p></td><td><p>72</p></td><td><p>74</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>February</p></td><td><p>49</p></td><td><p>73</p></td><td><p>54</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>March</p></td><td><p>55</p></td><td><p>53</p></td><td><p>55</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>April</p></td><td><p>48</p></td><td><p>46</p></td><td><p>56</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>May</p></td><td><p>51</p></td><td><p>52</p></td><td><p>66</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>June</p></td><td><p>50</p></td><td><p>46</p></td><td><p>71</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>July</p></td><td><p>51</p></td><td><p>44</p></td><td><p>66</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>August</p></td><td><p>39</p></td><td><p>46</p></td><td><p>61</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>September</p></td><td><p>33</p></td><td><p>44</p></td><td><p>63</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>October</p></td><td><p>41</p></td><td><p>38</p></td><td><p>51</p></td></tr><tr><td><p><strong>Total</strong></p></td><td><p><strong>512</strong></p></td><td><p><strong>683</strong></p></td><td><p><strong>796</strong></p></td></tr></tbody></table><p>During 1 October 2015 - 25 October 2016 the UK has conducted a total of 784 airstrikes within Iraqi territory. These are detailed as follows:</p><p> </p><table><tbody><tr><td><p><strong>2015</strong></p></td><td><p> </p></td></tr><tr><td><p>October</p></td><td><p>18</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>November</p></td><td><p>57</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>December</p></td><td><p>86</p></td></tr><tr><td><p><strong>2016</strong></p></td><td><p> </p></td></tr><tr><td><p>January</p></td><td><p>97</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>February</p></td><td><p>60</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>March</p></td><td><p>67</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>April</p></td><td><p>70</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>May</p></td><td><p>69</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>June</p></td><td><p>77</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>July</p></td><td><p>44</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>August</p></td><td><p>42</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>September</p></td><td><p>51</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>October</p></td><td><p>46</p></td></tr><tr><td><p><strong>Total</strong></p></td><td><p><strong>784</strong></p></td></tr></tbody></table><p> </p><p> </p><p>These strike numbers are constantly reviewed and updated by the Coalition to ensure records are as complete and as accurate as possible. As such, past and future statements regarding statistics may differ to those given here.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p>","Hemel Hempstead","Mike Penning",,"2016-10-27T15:20:57.203Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/607511/answer","Biography information for Sir Mike Penning","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/607511/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/607511/answer",,,,,"11","Defence","Defence","2016-10-21","Iraq: Military Intervention","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Defence, what estimate he has made of the number of (a) missions flown and (b) air strikes the armed forces have conducted within Iraqi territory in each of the last 12 months; and if he will make a statement.","false","Biography information for Mr Jim Cunningham","Coventry South","Mr Jim Cunningham","49740"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/607512","Ministry of Defence","false","2016-10-28","<p>Intermediate Level Waste (ILW) is the only type of waste from submarines that will require the use of a Geological Disposal Facility (GDF). A facility for the interim storage of ILW has been arranged at Capenhurst in Cheshire until the proposed GDF is available from 2040. In line with Government guidance, the interim ILW store will have a design life of at least 100 years - considerably longer than it is anticipated will be required.</p>","West Worcestershire","Harriett Baldwin",,"2016-10-28T13:08:19.81Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/607512/answer","Biography information for Harriett Baldwin","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/607512/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/607512/answer",,,,,"11","Defence","Defence","2016-10-21","Nuclear Submarines: Decommissioning","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Defence, what contingency plans his Department has for the decommissioning of nuclear-powered submarines if a suitable geological disposal facility is not identified.","false","Biography information for Steven Paterson","Stirling","Steven Paterson","49795"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/607513","Ministry of Defence","false","2016-10-28","<p>There are 12 submarines in laid-up storage in Her Majesty's Naval Base Devonport and seven at Rosyth Dockyard. Under the Submarine Dismantling Project (SDP) one submarine will commence 'Initial Dismantling' at Rosyth later in 2016, subject to regulatory permissions, to refine the process.</p><p>While laid-up, the submarines are subject to regular maintenance and checks by both the Ministry of Defence and regulators, and pose no additional risk to workers or members of the public.</p>","West Worcestershire","Harriett Baldwin",,"2016-10-28T13:08:51.687Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/607513/answer","Biography information for Harriett Baldwin","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/607513/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/607513/answer",,,,,"11","Defence","Defence","2016-10-21","Nuclear Submarines: Decommissioning","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Defence, how many nuclear-powered submarines are waiting for decommissioning work to be (a) commenced and (b) completed.","false","Biography information for Steven Paterson","Stirling","Steven Paterson","49796"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/607514","Department for Education","false","2016-10-31","<p>All schools and early years settings in England have a duty to keep children safe. As part of that duty we expect them to keep their health and safety policies under review and up-to-date.</p><p> </p><p>Working with ‘Action for Children’ we have brought the Department of Health’s recent alert on the dangers associated with the use of electrical socket covers to the attention of early years providers in England. ‘Action for Children’ has published a notice, via the Foundation Years website, about the use of electrical socket covers in early years provision in England. This is available at: <a href="http://www.foundationyears.org.uk/2016/10/dfe-note-on-the-use-of-electrical-plug-socket-coversinserts-in-early-years-provision-in-england/" target="_blank">www.foundationyears.org.uk/2016/10/dfe-note-on-the-use-of-electrical-plug-socket-coversinserts-in-early-years-provision-in-england</a>. ‘Action for Children’ has also published the information in a newsletter to early years providers.</p><p> </p><p>We are currently reviewing our health and safety advice for schools, and will consider whether to include a similar reference in a future addition of this advice as part of this work.</p>","Bognor Regis and Littlehampton","Nick Gibb",,"2016-10-31T17:01:41.723Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/607514/answer","Biography information for Nick Gibb","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/607514/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/607514/answer",,,,,"60","Education","Education","2016-10-21","Schools: Electrical Safety","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Education, what steps she is taking to ensure that early years settings and schools are aware that socket covers should not be inserted in BS 1363 sockets.","false","Biography information for Ian Murray","Edinburgh South","Ian Murray","49797"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/607515","Department for Education","false","2016-11-01","<p>We routinely publish all open academy details and academy projects in development.</p><p>These details can be easily accessed online and can be found here: <a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/publications/open-academies-and-academy-projects-in-development" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/government/publications/open-academies-and-academy-projects-in-development</a></p><p>The <em>Sponsored Pipeline</em> tab features a list of Sponsored academy projects currently in progress, the local authority in which they are located and, where applicable, the agreed sponsor.</p><p>We do not hold data on the time taken to match a sponsor with a school.</p>","Crewe and Nantwich","Edward Timpson","49708 ; 49710","2016-11-01T14:19:55.727Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/607515/answer","Biography information for Edward Timpson","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/607515/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/607515/answer",,,,,"60","Education","Education","2016-10-21","Academies: Sponsorship","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Education, how long, on average, it took to match sponsors with schools where an Academy Order was made in each year before the Education and Adoption Act 2016 came into force.","false","Biography information for Heidi Alexander","Lewisham East","Heidi Alexander","49751"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/607518","Department for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","false","2016-10-27","<p>The Department has regular meetings and conversations with retailer stakeholder groups and representatives from the packaging industry, including representatives of supermarkets. The Department also works through the Waste and Resources Action Programme (WRAP) on wide-ranging initiatives aimed at increasing recycling. Many of these initiatives, including the Courtauld Commitment, involve supermarkets.</p><p> </p><p> </p>","Suffolk Coastal","Dr Thérèse Coffey",,"2016-10-27T13:18:26.03Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/607518/answer","Biography information for Dr Thérèse  Coffey","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/607518/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/607518/answer",,,,,"13","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","2016-10-21","Packaging: Recycling","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs, what meetings her Department has had with supermarkets to discuss ensuring their packaging for produce and goods is recyclable.","false","Biography information for Nick Smith","Blaenau Gwent","Nick Smith","49792"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/607522","Department for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","false","2016-10-31","<p>Selection and notification of sites of special scientific interest (SSSIs) is a matter for Natural England. Natural England has published its current designations programme on GOV.UK (https://www.gov.uk/government/publications/natural-england-designations-programme-for-areas-sites-and-trails) and this includes several areas that host lowland grassland habitats. Natural England will continue to implement the <em>Guidelines for the selection of biological SSSIs</em>, as appropriate.</p>","Suffolk Coastal","Dr Thérèse Coffey",,"2016-10-31T10:37:22.69Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/607522/answer","Biography information for Dr Thérèse  Coffey","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/607522/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/607522/answer",,,,,"13","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","2016-10-21","Sites of Special Scientific Interest: Grasslands","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs, what plans her Department has to implement the Guidelines for Selection of Biological SSSIs, revised in 2014, on extending the protection for the rarest and most vulnerable lowland grasslands to all sites that meet the criteria.","false","Biography information for Dame Cheryl Gillan","Chesham and Amersham","Mrs Cheryl Gillan","49785"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/607523","Department for Communities and Local Government","false","2016-10-26","<p>The Government will determine how best to use any additional benefit received from the European Union Solidarity Fund once the amount of any award is known.</p>","Brigg and Goole","Andrew Percy",,"2016-10-26T14:22:46.417Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/607523/answer","Biography information for Andrew Percy","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/607523/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/607523/answer",,,,,"7","Communities and Local Government","Communities and Local Government","2016-10-21","Floods: EU Grants and Loans","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Communities and Local Government, how his Department plans to distribute money awarded by the European Solidarity Fund to flood-affected communities in the event that funds are awarded.","false","Biography information for Mr Jamie Reed","Copeland","Mr Jamie Reed","49807"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/607524","Department for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","false","2016-10-26","<p>I visited Keswick on 9 August 2016 and met members of the Keswick Flood Action Group. I saw and heard about both the impact of the winter floods and the programme of work on flooding prevention and resilience enhancement.</p><p> </p><p>I do not have another visit scheduled but I would be glad to meet the hon. Member for Copeland and Keswick representatives next time. Meanwhile, I am keen to support the good work that the Cumbria Flood Partnership and all local parties are doing on flood prevention and preparedness for the coming winter.</p><p> </p>","Suffolk Coastal","Dr Thérèse Coffey",,"2016-10-26T14:40:42.49Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/607524/answer","Biography information for Dr Thérèse  Coffey","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/607524/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/607524/answer",,,,,"13","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","2016-10-21","Flood Control: Copeland","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs, if she will visit Keswick to meet the Keswick Flood Action Group, the Keswick Town Council and the hon. Member for Copeland to discuss flood prevention.","false","Biography information for Mr Jamie Reed","Copeland","Mr Jamie Reed","49805"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/607525","Department for International Trade","false","2016-11-01","<p>Following her appointment on 13 July 2016 the Prime Minister established the Department for International Trade (DIT). Until such time as a transfer of functions order establishes my Rt hon Friend the Secretary of State for International Trade as a corporation sole, DIT remains a unified Foreign and Commonwealth Office (FCO) and Department for Business, Energy &amp; Industrial Strategy (BEIS) department for accounting purposes. The transfer of functions order (No 2016/ 992) laid on 19 October 2016 will come into effect on 9 November 2016.</p><p>DIT is a new Department and is in the process of establishing a separate and distinct budget for its operating costs. This will be shared with Parliament through the Autumn Statement and Supplementary Estimates.</p>","Wyre Forest","Mark Garnier","49739","2016-11-01T13:05:10.137Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/607525/answer","Biography information for Mark Garnier","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/607525/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/607525/answer",,,,,"202","International Trade","International Trade","2016-10-21","Department for International Trade: Public Expenditure","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for International Trade, with reference to the Answer of 10 October 2016 to Question 46333, how much has been spent on the functions of the Department for International Trade; and what estimate he has made of how much will be spent on those functions by the end of the current fiscal year.","false","Biography information for Diana Johnson","Kingston upon Hull North","Diana Johnson","49738"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/607526","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2016-10-31","The UK plays a full and active role in the UN First Committee on disarmament and international security. We are considering nearly 70 resolutions covering the whole spectrum of First Committee activity working with other States to prevent proliferation and to make progress towards multilateral nuclear disarmament.","Rutland and Melton","Sir Alan Duncan",,"2016-10-31T16:13:45.4Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/607526/answer","Biography information for Sir Alan Duncan","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/607526/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/607526/answer",,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2016-10-21","Nuclear Weapons: Arms Control","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Foreign and Commonwealth Affairs, what role he expects the UK to play in discussions at the UN General Assembly on multilateral nuclear disarmament; and if he will make a statement.","false","Biography information for Ronnie Cowan","Inverclyde","Ronnie Cowan","49768"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/607527","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2016-10-31","<p>Our Ambassador to Bahrain most recently raised the case of Nabeel Rajeb with the Bahraini Foreign Minister, Sheikh Khalid Bin Ahmad Al Khalifa, on 17 October. An Official from our Embassy in Bahrain has attended all of the hearings to date, including most recently on 6 October. We will continue to monitor the case closely.</p>","Bournemouth East","Mr Tobias Ellwood",,"2016-10-31T14:27:21.833Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/607527/answer","Biography information for Mr Tobias Ellwood","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/607527/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/607527/answer",,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2016-10-21","Nabeel Rajab","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Foreign and Commonwealth Affairs, pursuant to the Answer of 12 September 2016 to Question 45526, what representations he has received on the new charge brought against Nabeel Rajab by authorities in Bahrain.","false","Biography information for Margaret Ferrier","Rutherglen and Hamilton West","Margaret Ferrier","49777"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/607528","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2016-10-31","The Foreign Secretary, my Rt Hon. Friend the Member for Uxbridge and South Ruislip (Mr Johnson) has had discussions with a number of counterparts on the important issue of multilateral nuclear disarmament. The UK Government firmly believes that the best way to achieve a world without nuclear weapons is through gradual disarmament, negotiated using a step-by-step aproach and within the framework of the Nuclear non-Proliferation Treaty.","Rutland and Melton","Sir Alan Duncan",,"2016-10-31T16:22:26.833Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/607528/answer","Biography information for Sir Alan Duncan","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/607528/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/607528/answer",,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2016-10-21","Nuclear Weapons: Arms Control","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Foreign and Commonwealth Affairs, what discussions he has had with his counterparts in other (a) NATO member states and (b) Commonwealth countries on the upcoming discussions at the UN General Assembly on multilateral nuclear disarmament; and if he will make a statement.","false","Biography information for Ronnie Cowan","Inverclyde","Ronnie Cowan","49770"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/607529","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2016-10-27","<p>​We have already begun building up an enlarged Commonwealth team to deliver an ambitious, UK-hosted Commonwealth Heads of Government Meeting in 2018, both in policy and event management terms. We will continue to use our network of High Commissioners overseas in the other 51 Member States, bilateral desks in London, together with close cross-Departmental working to further our efforts on issues related to the Commonwealth.</p>","Bournemouth East","Mr Tobias Ellwood",,"2016-10-27T10:42:02.777Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/607529/answer","Biography information for Mr Tobias Ellwood","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/607529/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/607529/answer",,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2016-10-21","Foreign and Commonwealth Office: Staff","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Foreign and Commonwealth Affairs, what plans he has to increase the number of officials of his Department who work on issues related to the Commonwealth.","false","Biography information for Sir Hugo Swire","East Devon","Sir Hugo Swire","49762"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/607530","Department of Health","false","2016-10-26","<p>Clinical commissioning groups are responsible for commissioning mental health services that meet the needs of their local populations and take into account the health inequalities that may be experienced.</p><p> </p><p>The Equality Act 2010 makes it unlawful for any health provider to discriminate against a person on the basis of protected characteristic, including sexual orientation. The Mental Health Act 1983 Code of Practice makes it clear that mental health providers must adhere to the Public Sector Equality Duty created by the Equalities Act 2010. The Duty requires National Health Service commissioners, NHS providers and local authorities must have due regard to the need to:</p><p>- eliminate unlawful discrimination, harassment and victimisation;</p><p>- advance equality of opportunity between people who share a protected characteristic and those who do not; and</p><p>- foster good relations between people who share a protected characteristic and those who do not.</p><p> </p><p>We welcomed the recommendation in the Five Year Forward View for Mental Health to appoint a national Equalities Champion with a specific remit to tackle mental health inequalities across the health system and through cross-Government action. We are working with our stakeholders to progress this recommendation.</p><p> </p><p>We would also expect NHS commissioners and mental health providers to implement best practice guidance such the Joint Commissioning Panel for Mental Health guidance on commissioning public mental health services (2015):</p><p> </p><p><a href="http://www.jcpmh.info/wp-content/uploads/jcpmh-publicmentalhealth-guide.pdf" target="_blank">http://www.jcpmh.info/wp-content/uploads/jcpmh-publicmentalhealth-guide.pdf</a></p><p> </p><p>Public Health England also published an action plan to set out how it is tackling inequalities in gay and bisexual men, Public Health England action plan 2015-16: Promoting the health and wellbeing of gay, bisexual and other men who have sex with men:</p><p> </p><p><a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/uploads/system/uploads/attachment_data/file/401005/PHEMSMActionPlan.pdf" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/government/uploads/system/uploads/attachment_data/file/401005/PHEMSMActionPlan.pdf</a></p>","Oxford West and Abingdon","Nicola Blackwood",,"2016-10-26T16:22:14.94Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/607530/answer","Biography information for Baroness Blackwood of North Oxford","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/607530/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/607530/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2016-10-21","Mental Health Services: LGBT People","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, what steps he is taking to ensure mental health services are accessible to LGBT people.","false","Biography information for Luciana Berger","Liverpool, Wavertree","Luciana Berger","49755"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/607531","Department of Health","false","2016-10-26","<p>This information is not available in the format requested.</p>","Oxford West and Abingdon","Nicola Blackwood",,"2016-10-26T16:24:43.617Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/607531/answer","Biography information for Baroness Blackwood of North Oxford","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/607531/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/607531/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2016-10-21","Body Dysmorphic Disorder","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, how many people were treated for body dysmorphic disorder in (a) Liverpool Wavertree constituency, (b) Liverpool, (c) England and (d) each region in each year since 2010.","false","Biography information for Luciana Berger","Liverpool, Wavertree","Luciana Berger","49756"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/607532","Department of Health","false","2016-10-27","<p>The Department provided grant funding in 2013-16 to Together for Short Lives, the organisation supporting children’s hospices, to support the Transition Taskforce. The Taskforce provides guidance and training that supports good transitions locally between children’s and adult services for those with life-limiting conditions or needing palliative care.</p><p> </p><p>NHS England is continuing to prioritise funding for the children’s hospice grants programme at the current level. NHS England has been engaging with children’s hospices through Together for Short Lives prior to a consultation on the allocation method for the 2017-18 grant.</p>","Warrington South","David Mowat","49750","2016-10-27T14:09:41.18Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/607532/answer","Biography information for David Mowat","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/607532/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/607532/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2016-10-21","Hospices: Children and Young People","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, what plans he has to provide support to children's hospices which extend their services for young adults.","false","Biography information for Jeremy Lefroy","Stafford","Jeremy Lefroy","49749"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/607533","Department of Health","false","2016-10-27","<p>The Department provided grant funding in 2013-16 to Together for Short Lives, the organisation supporting children’s hospices, to support the Transition Taskforce. The Taskforce provides guidance and training that supports good transitions locally between children’s and adult services for those with life-limiting conditions or needing palliative care.</p><p> </p><p>NHS England is continuing to prioritise funding for the children’s hospice grants programme at the current level. NHS England has been engaging with children’s hospices through Together for Short Lives prior to a consultation on the allocation method for the 2017-18 grant.</p>","Warrington South","David Mowat","49749","2016-10-27T14:09:41.227Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/607533/answer","Biography information for David Mowat","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/607533/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/607533/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2016-10-21","Hospices: Children","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, what plans he has to formalise the children's hospice grant for 2017-18.","false","Biography information for Jeremy Lefroy","Stafford","Jeremy Lefroy","49750"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/607534","Department of Health","true","2016-10-26","<p>The Care Quality Commission (CQC) is the independent regulator of health and adult social care in England. The CQC makes decisions on whether to register providers based on the requirements of the Health and Social Care Act 2008.</p><p> </p><p>The CQC provides assurance that all registered providers are meeting the relevant standards and then through a system of monitoring and ongoing inspection to make sure that standards are being maintained.</p><p> </p><p>The CQC has advised us that for the period July, August and September 2016 Coperforma held the contract with High Weald Lewes Haven Clinical Commissioning Group (CCG) to provide Patient Transport Services to the population of Brighton and elsewhere. The CQC has confirmed that Coperforma were registered to provide patient transport services during the period in question.</p><p> </p><p>The CQC has confirmed that Docklands Medical Services Ltd was not registered to provide patient transport services during the period in question. When it is brought to the attention of the CQC that a provider may have been delivering a regulated activity without registration, they investigate. If the CQC finds evidence to show that regulated activity is or has been delivered whilst unregistered then the CQC may prosecute. It is an offence under the Health and Social Care Act 2008 to carry out a regulated activity - in this case patient transport services - without being registered with the CQC. The CQC is investigating whether an offence has been committed.</p><p> </p><p>The Department understands that <ins class="ministerial">when</ins> the High Weald Lewes Havens CCG identified that the <ins class="ministerial">CQC registration in question related </ins><del class="ministerial">registered provider Coperforma had subcontracted service delivery</del> to Docklands Medical Services <ins class="ministerial">(London)</ins> <del class="ministerial">Ltd</del> <ins class="ministerial">rather than Docklands Medical Services Ltd, they contacted </ins><del class="ministerial">and immediately instructed</del> Coperforma <ins class="ministerial">asking them to confirm the relevant CQC registration status.</ins><del class="ministerial"> to cease using Docklands Medical Services Limited as a subcontractor. This was immediately actioned by Coperforma. </del></p><p><ins class="ministerial">I have also asked NHS England to investigate this provision of transport services during July, August and September 2016.</ins></p>","Ludlow","Mr Philip Dunne",,"2016-10-26T18:02:42.72Z","2016-11-01T12:45:02.49Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/607534/answer","Biography information for Mr Philip Dunne","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/607534/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/607534/answer","Ludlow","Mr Philip Dunne","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/607534/answer/previousversion/16824","Biography information for Mr Philip Dunne","17","Health","Health","2016-10-21","Docklands Medical Services","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, whether Docklands Medical Services Ltd were registered with the Care Quality Commission for the provision of patient transport services during July, August and September 2016; and if he will make a statement.","false","Biography information for Caroline Lucas","Brighton, Pavilion","Caroline Lucas","49779"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/607535","Department of Health","false","2016-10-31","<p>NHS Improvement and NHS England wrote to all National Health Service providers on 17 December 2015 to ask them to conduct a self-assessment of their rate of avoidable mortality.</p><p> </p><p>On the same date, my Rt. hon. Friend the Secretary of State gave a Written Ministerial Statement (<a href="http://www.parliament.uk/business/publications/written-questions-answers-statements/written-statement/Commons/2015-03-17/HCWS421/" target="_blank">HCWS421</a>) to the House in which he announced that the Care Quality Commission would undertake a wider review into the investigation of deaths and how the NHS learns from them across all types of NHS trust (acute, mental health and community trusts) in different parts of the country.</p><p> </p><p>We intend to respond to the publication of that review setting out our plans for ensuring that the NHS reports and learns from such incidents, including how avoidable mortality is recorded and generates learning at a local level.</p>","Ludlow","Mr Philip Dunne",,"2016-10-31T17:39:34.477Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/607535/answer","Biography information for Mr Philip Dunne","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/607535/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/607535/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2016-10-21","Patients: Death","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, what his Department's policy is on requiring NHS trusts to record avoidable deaths; and if he will make a statement.","false","Biography information for Graham Stringer","Blackley and Broughton","Graham Stringer","49781"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/607536","Department of Health","false","2016-10-26","<p>The Government is committed to proportionate regulation of healthcare professions. Whilst statutory regulation is sometimes necessary where significant risks to users of services cannot be mitigated in other ways, it is not always the most proportionate or effective means of assuring the safe and effective care of service users.</p><p> </p><p>Occupational and professional groups that are not subject to statutory regulation, such as Dance Movement Psychotherapists, may consider setting up a voluntary register. The Professional Standards Authority accredits those registers that meet its standards, providing patients, the public and employers with assurance about the standards and competence of registrants.</p>","Ludlow","Mr Philip Dunne",,"2016-10-26T09:31:24.233Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/607536/answer","Biography information for Mr Philip Dunne","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/607536/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/607536/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2016-10-21","Psychiatry","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, if he will make it his policy to regulate dance movement psychotherapy.","false","Biography information for Luciana Berger","Liverpool, Wavertree","Luciana Berger","49753"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/607537","Department of Health","false","2016-10-26","<p>General practitioners (GPs) are independent contractors who hold contracts with NHS England to provide primary medical services for the National Health Service. Under the terms of their contract, GPs are required to provide certain medical reports or complete certain forms, such as those required to support a claim for incapacity benefit, free of charge to their registered patients.</p><p> </p><p>Outside of contractual requirements, GPs also provide a variety of other services which successive governments have regarded as private matters between the patient and the GP providing these services. In such cases, decisions on whether to charge a fee and the level of the fee charged are at the GP’s discretion. Where GPs intend to charge for services to patients, the British Medical Association advises them to forewarn patients, at the earliest opportunity, of the likely level of fees.</p>","Warrington South","David Mowat",,"2016-10-26T11:36:55.46Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/607537/answer","Biography information for David Mowat","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/607537/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/607537/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2016-10-21","General Practitioners: Fees and Charges","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, if he will make it his policy to set a limit on the amount GPs can charge patients for signing a debt and mental health evidence form.","false","Biography information for Luciana Berger","Liverpool, Wavertree","Luciana Berger","49754"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/607538","Department of Health","false","2016-10-26","<p>As at 20 October 2016 there were 550 people on the active liver transplant list.</p><p> </p><p>Waiting list figures can fluctuate daily as patients are removed or added to the transplant list as their condition improves or deteriorates.</p>","Oxford West and Abingdon","Nicola Blackwood",,"2016-10-26T16:23:52.873Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/607538/answer","Biography information for Baroness Blackwood of North Oxford","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/607538/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/607538/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2016-10-21","Liver Diseases: Transplant Surgery","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, how many people are on NHS waiting lists to receive a liver transplant.","false","Biography information for Mr Nigel Evans","Ribble Valley","Mr Nigel Evans","49812"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/607539","Department of Health","false","2016-10-26","<p>It is the responsibility of clinical commissioning groups (CCGs) to commission services to meet the needs of their populations, which will include services provided by National Health Service trusts and foundation trusts in most instances.</p><p> </p><p>The NHS Operational Planning and Contractual Guidance (authored by NHS England and NHS Improvement) provides guidance for CCGs to help commissioning. The Department would expect commissioners to take a range of information into account including population projections.</p><p> </p><p>A copy of the NHS Operational Planning and Contractual Guidance can be found at the following address:</p><p> </p><p><a href="https://www.england.nhs.uk/wp-content/uploads/2016/09/NHS-operational-planning-guidance-201617-201819.pdf" target="_blank">https://www.england.nhs.uk/wp-content/uploads/2016/09/NHS-operational-planning-guidance-201617-201819.pdf</a></p>","Warrington South","David Mowat",,"2016-10-26T11:37:41.733Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/607539/answer","Biography information for David Mowat","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/607539/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/607539/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2016-10-21","Health Services","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, what guidance his Department has given NHS trusts on the use of Office for National Statistics population projections for service planning.","false","Biography information for Mr Jamie Reed","Copeland","Mr Jamie Reed","49806"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/607540","Department of Health","false","2016-10-26","<p>There are currently no plans for an opt-out system for organ donation in England. Since 2008 donation in the United Kingdom has increased by 68% and transplants by 47%, by increasing the number of specialist nurses and strengthening the donation infrastructure. 2015/16 saw the highest ever deceased donor rate in the UK with 1,364 deceased donors resulting in 3,529 transplants.</p><p> </p><p>We continue to support work to further increase donation and transplantation rates, particularly promoting collaborative working amongst organisations and raising awareness of donation in the Black, Asian and Minority Ethnic communities to become donors.</p><p> </p><p>NHS Blood and Transplant launched a new UK–wide organ donation and transplantation strategy in July 2013. <em>Taking Organ Transplantation to 2020</em> identifies the action being taken to increase organ donation and transplantation.</p>","Oxford West and Abingdon","Nicola Blackwood",,"2016-10-26T16:23:08.877Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/607540/answer","Biography information for Baroness Blackwood of North Oxford","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/607540/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/607540/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2016-10-21","Organs: Donors","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, whether his Department has plans for an opt-out system for organ donation across the UK.","false","Biography information for Mr Nigel Evans","Ribble Valley","Mr Nigel Evans","49808"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/607541","Department of Health","false","2016-10-26","<p>Clinical Reference Groups (CRG) are currently undertaking a process of recruitment. Once all appointments have been made, a full list of members for each CRG will be published on NHS England’s website. However, for the Specialised Neurosciences CRG, the Chair and Lead CRG Commissioner have been confirmed as Adrian Williams and Jacquie Kemp respectively.</p>","Warrington South","David Mowat",,"2016-10-26T11:04:31.153Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/607541/answer","Biography information for David Mowat","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/607541/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/607541/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2016-10-21","Neuroscience Clinical Reference Group","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, if he will list the members of the neuroscience clinical reference group of NHS England.","false","Biography information for Dame Cheryl Gillan","Chesham and Amersham","Mrs Cheryl Gillan","49799"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/607542","Department of Health","false","2016-10-31","<p>This information is not available centrally. The Better Health Programme is a locally-led programme run by the National Health Service in Darlington, Durham and Tees. Information on the number of people who registered for and attended engagement events can be obtained from the NHS locally.</p>","Ludlow","Mr Philip Dunne",,"2016-10-31T16:19:55.033Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/607542/answer","Biography information for Mr Philip Dunne","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/607542/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/607542/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2016-10-21","Health Services","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, how many people have (a) registered for and (b) attended events as part of the Better Health Programme.","false","Biography information for Jenny Chapman","Darlington","Jenny Chapman","49787"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/607543","Home Office","false","2016-10-31","<p>All individuals are referred to the UK authorities by the French non-governmental organisation, France terre d'asile and are then interviewed by French and UK officials.</p><p>Where credible and clear documentary evidence of age is not available, trained officials will use criteria including physical appearance and demeanour to assess age as part of the interview process.</p><p>Where we believe someone is significantly over the age of 18, they will be refused transfer to the UK as a child. The Home Office does not use dental x-rays to determine an individual’s age; the British Dental Association has described them as inaccurate, inappropriate and unethical.</p>","Scarborough and Whitby","Mr Robert Goodwill",,"2016-10-31T16:42:46.2Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/607543/answer","Biography information for Mr Robert Goodwill","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/607543/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/607543/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2016-10-21","Refugees: Children","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, what steps her Department is taking to ensure that children coming to the UK as refugees from Calais are under 18 years olds.","false","Biography information for Steve Double","St Austell and Newquay","Steve Double","49790"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/607544","Home Office","false","2016-11-03","<p>The Home Office publishes the Immigration Statistics release each quarter.</p><p>The requested information is available in table as_08, in volume 3 of the asylum data tables:</p><p>https://www.gov.uk/government/uploads/system/uploads/attachment_data/file/546760/asylum3-q2-2016-tabs.ods</p><p>A copy of the latest release, Immigration Statistics April to June 2016, is available from:</p><p>https://www.gov.uk/government/publications/immigration-statistics-april-to-june2016/asylum</p>","Scarborough and Whitby","Mr Robert Goodwill",,"2016-11-03T17:48:53.74Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/607544/answer","Biography information for Mr Robert Goodwill","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/607544/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/607544/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2016-10-21","Asylum: Children","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, how many (a) male and (b) female unaccompanied children arrived in the UK seeking asylum in each of the last three years for which figures are available.","false","Biography information for David T. C. Davies","Monmouth","David T. C. Davies","49744"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/607545","Home Office","false","2016-10-26","<p>The Home Office was part of the steering group of an Equalities and Human Rights Commission project to tackle homophobic, biphobic and transphobic hate crime, which ended earlier this year.</p><p>As a result, we have committed to work with organisations such as the anti-violence charity Galop to develop resources that specifically meet the needs of Lesbian, Gay, Bisexual and Trans (LGBT) communities. We are also sharing existing good practice, including across the LGBT Hate Crime Network which was established by the project and is made up of over 30 groups across the country.</p><p>The cross-Government Hate Crime Action Plan, developed following consultation with a number of LGBT groups, contains actions designed to tackle hate crime against LGB&amp;T people. This includes an assessment of the levels of homophobic bullying in schools, renewed CPS legal guidance on homophobic, biphobic and transphobic crime and funding for community groups who are working to tackle hate crime, including homophobic, biphobic and transphobic hate crime.</p>","Truro and Falmouth","Sarah Newton",,"2016-10-26T16:50:42.127Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/607545/answer","Biography information for Sarah Newton","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/607545/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/607545/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2016-10-21","Homophobia: Hate Crime","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, what steps she has taken to reduce homophobic hate crimes since January 2016.","false","Biography information for Luciana Berger","Liverpool, Wavertree","Luciana Berger","49752"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/607546","Department of Health","false","2016-10-31","<p>We have not had any discussions with Eastbourne Borough Council about Beachy Head as a place used by people to take their own life. Local authorities are responsible for local suicide prevention by working with local agencies to implement local suicide prevention plans.</p><p> </p><p>Public Health England (PHE) published guidance in 2015, ‘Preventing suicides in public places: A practice resource’, to support local areas taking action in places known to be used for suicide:</p><p> </p><p><a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/latest?departments%5B%5D=public-health-england" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/government/latest?departments%5B%5D=public-health-england</a></p><p> </p><p>PHE also published refreshed guidance on 25 October, ‘Local suicide prevention planning: a practice resource’, to support local areas to implement multi-agency suicide prevention plans which will bring together all local agencies to work collaboratively to prevent suicide:</p><p> </p><p><a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/uploads/system/uploads/attachment_data/file/562280/PHE_local_suicide_prevention_planning_a_practice_resource.pdf" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/government/uploads/system/uploads/attachment_data/file/562280/PHE_local_suicide_prevention_planning_a_practice_resource.pdf</a></p>","Oxford West and Abingdon","Nicola Blackwood",,"2016-10-31T17:46:40.34Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/607546/answer","Biography information for Baroness Blackwood of North Oxford","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/607546/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/607546/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2016-10-21","Suicide: Beachy Head","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, what discussions his Department has had with Eastbourne Borough Council on steps to deter or prevent people from taking their own life on Beachy Head.","false","Biography information for Sir Henry Bellingham","North West Norfolk","Sir Henry Bellingham","49742"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/607547","Home Office","false","2016-11-01","<p>Potential Victims who are recorded in the National Referral Mechanism Statistics (NRM) statistics as having suffered an unknown type of exploitation are identified and referred through the same process as other victims. The breakdown of agencies who referred them to the NRM are included in published statistics, data for which is derived from initial referral forms. An ‘unknown’ categorisation can result from missing or incomplete information on this form, which may be collected at a later stage as part of the ongoing assessment and safeguarding of the potential victim concerned.</p>","Truro and Falmouth","Sarah Newton",,"2016-11-01T16:26:55.74Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/607547/answer","Biography information for Sarah Newton","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/607547/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/607547/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2016-10-21","Slavery","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, how potential victims of trafficking whose type of exploitation is recorded as unknown in the National Referral Mechanism Statistics, end of year summary 2015, published on 11 February 2016 were identified; and if she will make a statement.","false","Biography information for Fiona Mactaggart","Slough","Fiona Mactaggart","49737"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/607548","Home Office","false","2016-11-03","<p>The process of transferring unaccompanied children from Calais to the UK under the Dublin III Regulation is an ongoing operational matter and the Home Office will provide an update in due course.</p>","Scarborough and Whitby","Mr Robert Goodwill",,"2016-11-03T17:43:51.11Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/607548/answer","Biography information for Mr Robert Goodwill","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/607548/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/607548/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2016-10-21","Refugees: Children","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, how many of the unaccompanied children that have arrived in the UK from Calais under the Dublin III Regulation are (a) male and (b) female.","false","Biography information for Tim Loughton","East Worthing and Shoreham","Tim Loughton","49778"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/607549","Home Office","false","2016-11-03","<p>The Home Office received representations from a number of bodies be-tween 2012 and 2014 about the possible use of dental tests to establish the age of people claiming asylum. The view of many of those making representations was that the use of dental tests for this purpose would be unreliable, inappropriate and unethical.</p>","Scarborough and Whitby","Mr Robert Goodwill",,"2016-11-03T17:47:23.39Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/607549/answer","Biography information for Mr Robert Goodwill","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/607549/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/607549/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2016-10-21","Asylum: Age","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, whether her Department received any representations from King's College Dental School, between 2012 and 2014, on the use of dental tests to establish the age of people claiming asylum.","false","Biography information for David T. C. Davies","Monmouth","David T. C. Davies","49763"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/607550","House of Commons Commission","false","2016-10-31","<p>The Trainline ticket machine situated in the Parliamentary Travel Office has been unable to print tickets on six separate days since September 2014, the latest period being 17–19 October 2016. The machine is owned by Trainline but it is CTM’s responsibility to ensure that they report any faults so that they can be fixed quickly and efficiently.</p><p>The ticket machine situated in the Members’ Centre in Portcullis House is maintained by IPSA and therefore the Commission does not hold records on the operation of that machine. However, officials are aware that the machine has been out of service since the beginning of September 2016.</p>","Carshalton and Wallington","Tom Brake",,"2016-10-31T17:15:54.833Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/607550/answer","Biography information for Tom Brake","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/607550/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/607550/answer",,,,,"18","House of Commons Commission","House of Commons Commission","2016-10-21","Parliamentary Travel Office","1","House of Commons","To ask the Rt. hon. Member for Carshalton and Wallington representing the House of Commons Commission, on how many days under the current Travel Office contract the ticket machines situated in the House have been unable to print hon. Members' travel tickets.","false","Biography information for Frank Field","Birkenhead","Frank Field","49746"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/607551","Department for International Development","false","2016-10-27","<p>The UK is supporting hundreds of thousands of people displaced by the Syria crisis in Syria, Jordan, Lebanon and Turkey. We also provide support, assistance and protection for over 5 million Palestinian refugees in Gaza, the West Bank and the region. In Africa, our programmes support over a million refugees, with a focus on Kenya, Ethiopia and Uganda. The Secretary of State recently visited Kenya and saw how UK support for refugees is creating trading opportunities and sustainable livelihoods closer to home. The UK has announced a further £20 million to help voluntary, humane and safe returns for Somali refugees in Kenya, and £15 million towards a UN Appeal to support an expected one million displaced people in Afghanistan, including returning refugees.</p>","Penrith and The Border","Rory Stewart",,"2016-10-27T14:56:13.857Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/607551/answer","Biography information for Rory Stewart","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/607551/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/607551/answer",,,,,"20","International Development","International Development","2016-10-21","Refugees","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for International Development, pursuant to the Answer of 20 October 2016 to Question 48875, how many refugees her Department has helped to remain in, or stay as close as possible to, their countries of origin.","false","Biography information for Frank Field","Birkenhead","Frank Field","49793"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/607552","Department for International Development","false","2016-10-26","<p>The UK Government is playing a leading role in improving energy access in developing countries. DFID has a range of programmes which are working with developing countries to ensure renewable energy markets work effectively as well as supporting energy businesses to grow, and providing consumers with access to funding to buy solar goods. For example, our Energy Access Ventures programme is investing in off-grid electric and we are delivering green mini-grid solutions across Africa.</p><p>Through the UK Government’s Energy Africa campaign we are working with solar firms to help them access the finance they need to expand their businesses, create jobs and help reach millions of people in Africa without electricity access</p>","Stockton South","James Wharton",,"2016-10-26T14:30:11.253Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/607552/answer","Biography information for James Wharton","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/607552/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/607552/answer",,,,,"20","International Development","International Development","2016-10-21","Developing Countries: Renewable Energy","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for International Development, what plans her Department has to increase investment in decentralised renewable energy in developing countries.","false","Biography information for Mr Nigel Evans","Ribble Valley","Mr Nigel Evans","49815"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/607553","Ministry of Justice","false","2016-10-31","<p>I refer the Hon member to my answer to PQ 46278.</p>","East Surrey","Mr Sam Gyimah",,"2016-10-31T16:38:37.317Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/607553/answer","Biography information for Mr Sam Gyimah","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/607553/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/607553/answer",,,,,"54","Justice","Justice","2016-10-21","Prisons: Education","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Justice, what recent steps her Department has taken to improve education in prisons.","false","Biography information for Mr Stewart Jackson","Peterborough","Mr Stewart Jackson","49741"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/607554","Ministry of Justice","false","2016-10-31","<p>Information about drivers who have not been disqualified from driving as a result of a court accepting that disqualification would lead to exceptional hardship is not held centrally and can only be obtained at disproportionate cost.</p><p>The Government is committed to making sure that sentencing for those who kill or cause serious injury on the roads is proportionate within the context of our wider sentencing framework. It is our intention to commence a consultation on driving offences and penalties before the end of the year.</p>","East Surrey","Mr Sam Gyimah","49748","2016-10-31T16:30:57.84Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/607554/answer","Biography information for Mr Sam Gyimah","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/607554/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/607554/answer",,,,,"54","Justice","Justice","2016-10-21","Driving: Licensing","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Justice, how many drivers have avoided disqualification from driving within the last year by pleading the loss of their licence would cause exceptional hardship.","false","Biography information for Ruth Cadbury","Brentford and Isleworth","Ruth Cadbury","49747"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/607555","Ministry of Justice","false","2016-10-31","<p>Information about drivers who have not been disqualified from driving as a result of a court accepting that disqualification would lead to exceptional hardship is not held centrally and can only be obtained at disproportionate cost.</p><p>The Government is committed to making sure that sentencing for those who kill or cause serious injury on the roads is proportionate within the context of our wider sentencing framework. It is our intention to commence a consultation on driving offences and penalties before the end of the year.</p>","East Surrey","Mr Sam Gyimah","49747","2016-10-31T16:30:57.903Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/607555/answer","Biography information for Mr Sam Gyimah","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/607555/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/607555/answer",,,,,"54","Justice","Justice","2016-10-21","Road Traffic Offences","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Justice, whether she plans to include legislation for exceptional hardship pleas within the forthcoming review of motoring offences and penalties.","false","Biography information for Ruth Cadbury","Brentford and Isleworth","Ruth Cadbury","49748"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/607556","Department for Transport","false","2016-10-26","<p>HS2, through both HS2 Ltd and its supply chain, has a target of creating 2,000 apprenticeship opportunities over the lifetime of the project, from a forecast average annual workforce of 11,000 (with a peak of 25,000).</p><p> </p><p>HS2 Ltd itself has to date provided five apprenticeships, though this is in the context that HS2 does not yet have Royal Assent and construction hasn’t yet started. Looking forward, it is anticipated that HS2 Ltd will bring in 36 apprentices a year based on an average workforce of 1,500.</p><p><strong> </strong></p><p>For the companies that will design and construct HS2 there will be requirements to deliver Skills, Employment and Education outcomes, including apprenticeships. In each of the major HS2 Ltd contracts, all bidders are assessed on their ability to deliver on these outcomes through the procurement process. Therefore, as HS2 enters its construction stage in 2017, apprenticeships are expected to increase rapidly.</p><p> </p>","Harrogate and Knaresborough","Andrew Jones",,"2016-10-26T15:49:47.837Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/607556/answer","Biography information for Andrew Jones","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/607556/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/607556/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2016-10-21","High Speed Two: Apprentices","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, how many apprenticeships have been provided to date by HS2 Ltd.","false","Biography information for Dame Cheryl Gillan","Chesham and Amersham","Mrs Cheryl Gillan","49798"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/607557","Department for Transport","false","2016-10-31","<p>The transport sector faces significant skills challenges driven by a range of factors including an ageing workforce, a lack of diversity, the introduction of new technologies (such as digital signalling in rail) and the sheer scale of our transport investment programme.</p><p> </p><p>The National Skills Academy for Rail (NSAR) has identified rail skills shortages in signalling and telecommunications, electrification and plant, traction and rolling stock of 10,000 people between 2014 and 2019.</p><p> </p><p>In response to these challenges, in August 2015 this Department appointed Crossrail chair Terry Morgan to develop the Transport Infrastructure Skills Strategy (TISS). The TISS was published in January 2016 and the Strategic Transport Apprenticeship Taskforce (STAT) was launched on 15 April 2016 as an employer-led group to oversee the delivery of the TISS recommendations andto address these skills shortages including through the delivery of 30,000 transport apprenticeships by 2020.</p><p> </p><p>The Taskforce has commissioned NSAR to update skills forecasts for both road and rail. This analysis is expected to be complete by the end of December this year.</p><p> </p><p>The National College for High Speed Rail will provide specialist vocational training to the next generation of engineers working on HS2 and beyond. Over 1,000 students are expected to graduate from the college each year.</p><p>Construction of the college is now officially underway and on course to open its doors to students in time for the start of the 2017-18 academic year.</p><p> </p><p>Both the existing UK construction and engineering workforce as well as new entrants, such as apprentices, will benefit from the training that will be provided by the new college. The college will tackle the engineering skills shortage that is one of the industry’s biggest barriers to sustainability, productivity and growth.</p><p> </p><p> </p>","Blackpool North and Cleveleys","Paul Maynard",,"2016-10-31T16:22:31.29Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/607557/answer","Biography information for Paul Maynard","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/607557/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/607557/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2016-10-21","Railways: Training","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, what estimate his Department has made of the shortage of people with rail engineering, environmental and construction skills.","false","Biography information for Dame Cheryl Gillan","Chesham and Amersham","Mrs Cheryl Gillan","49784"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/607558","Department for Transport","false","2016-10-31","<p>The legislation that provides for licensing of taxi and private hire vehicle services is enabling in its nature, giving local licensing authorities the discretion to set standards that they deem to be appropriate for their area. Rossendale Council has already made changes to the Taxi and Private Hire Vehicle application process to address the rapid rise in the number of drivers they license. Wherever a driver has been licensed, the licensing authority that issue that licence must have confirmed that the driver is a “fit and proper” person.</p><p> </p><p>To help licensing authorities set standards the Department for Transport issues Best Practice Guidance. In addition to this, the Government has also introduced an amendment to the Policing and Crime Bill that will make statutory all aspects of the guidance that are related to the safeguarding of children and vulnerable adults. Both parts of the guidance will be consulted on publicly once the Bill has received Royal Assent.</p>","Harrogate and Knaresborough","Andrew Jones",,"2016-10-31T17:39:43.053Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/607558/answer","Biography information for Andrew Jones","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/607558/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/607558/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2016-10-21","Taxis: Rossendale","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, pursuant to the Answer of 12 October 2016 to Question 46806 on taxis: licensing, what assessment he has made of the reasons for the increase in licence applications from Rossendale Borough Council between 2013 and 2015.","false","Biography information for Paul Blomfield","Sheffield Central","Paul Blomfield","49791"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/607559","Department for Transport","false","2016-10-27","<p>HS2 Ltd continues to use all feedback and recommendations made by the Residents’ Commissioner, including those made in published reports, to help improve the quality of its communication and engagement with communities affected by HS2 proposals.</p><p> </p><p>In response to recommendations made by the Residents’ Commissioner HS2 Ltd has, for example, expanded its community engagement teams to provide more localised support and information to affected communities, introduced a mobile unit which will have a wider reach where residents not able to attend HS2 Ltd-run events, and raised awareness of the package of HS2 property compensation and discretionary assistance schemes which are available.</p><p> </p>","Harrogate and Knaresborough","Andrew Jones",,"2016-10-27T13:34:57.6Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/607559/answer","Biography information for Andrew Jones","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/607559/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/607559/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2016-10-21","High Speed Two","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, how many of the recommendations made by the HS2 Ltd Residents' Commissioner in her published reports have been adopted in full by HS2 Ltd.","false","Biography information for Dame Cheryl Gillan","Chesham and Amersham","Mrs Cheryl Gillan","49783"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/607560","Department for Transport","false","2016-10-26","<p>Incentive payments were based on accrued estimates of the contractually obliged sums payable to the company’s Development Partner CH2M Hill and its Professional Service Contractors. These contractors have provided critical support to HS2 Ltd in its undertaking of both its preparatory works and its ongoing hybrid Bill management. Assessment is undertaken by a multi-disciplinary panel from across HS2 Ltd to consider the case made by each contractor as to the additional value provided over and above the original contracted scope.</p><p> </p><p>The accrued estimates accounted for in support of HS2 Ltd’s preparatory works are £1.4m, split over the following suppliers: CH2M Hill, Arup, Atkins, Capita Symons / Ineco, ERM / Temple / Mott McDonald, Mott.</p><p> </p>","Harrogate and Knaresborough","Andrew Jones",,"2016-10-26T15:00:56.667Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/607560/answer","Biography information for Andrew Jones","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/607560/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/607560/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2016-10-21","High Speed Two","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, with reference to the project management section of the High Speed Rail (Preparation) Act 2013 Expenditure Report, 1 April 2015 to 31 March 2016, what incentive payments were made to HS2 Ltd's development partners and professional services contractors; to whom such payments were made; and what exceptional performance was relevant in each such case.","false","Biography information for Dame Cheryl Gillan","Chesham and Amersham","Mrs Cheryl Gillan","49780"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/607561","Department for Transport","false","2016-10-27","<p>The Government has committed £52 million of capital cost up until the College opening. To date £12.3 million has been spent.</p>","Harrogate and Knaresborough","Andrew Jones",,"2016-10-27T13:30:20.777Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/607561/answer","Biography information for Andrew Jones","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/607561/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/607561/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2016-10-21","National College for High Speed Rail","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, what the total cost to the public purse has been to date of the National College for High Speed Rail.","false","Biography information for Dame Cheryl Gillan","Chesham and Amersham","Mrs Cheryl Gillan","49772"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/607562","Department for Transport","false","2016-10-27","<p>The college is due to open to students in September 2017.</p>","Harrogate and Knaresborough","Andrew Jones",,"2016-10-27T13:20:01.867Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/607562/answer","Biography information for Andrew Jones","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/607562/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/607562/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2016-10-21","National College for High Speed Rail","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, when the National College for High Speed Rail will be operational.","false","Biography information for Dame Cheryl Gillan","Chesham and Amersham","Mrs Cheryl Gillan","49786"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/607563","Department for Transport","false","2016-10-26","<p>The difference between the actual and budgeted cost per person was due to the mix of permanent and non-permanent workforce being different from that assumed during the budgeting process. This was reflective of the greater reliance required on non-permanent specialist support to quickly mobilise teams to undertake preparation for Early Works Contracts leading into Main Works.</p><p> </p>","Harrogate and Knaresborough","Andrew Jones",,"2016-10-26T14:57:27.017Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/607563/answer","Biography information for Andrew Jones","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/607563/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/607563/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2016-10-21","High Speed Two","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, with reference to paragraph 3.12 of the High Speed Rail (Preparation) Act 2013 Expenditure Report, 1 April 2015 to 31 March 2016, published by his Department in October 2016, if he will provide reasons for the difference between the actual and budgeted cost per person in the project management team.","false","Biography information for Dame Cheryl Gillan","Chesham and Amersham","Mrs Cheryl Gillan","49800"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/607564","Department for Transport","false","2016-10-26","<p>The £192.7m of the Land &amp; Property (L&amp;P) underspend shown in the High Speed Rail (Preparation) Act 2013 Expenditure Report for 1 April 2015 – 31 March 2016 was formed from two elements – strategic property acquisitions and compensation schemes, including providing discretionary assistance to home owners and small businesses.</p><p> </p><p>The majority of the total L&amp;P underspend was caused by delays in completing non-compensation scheme acquisitions. These are generally acquisitions of commercial properties and it is hard to accurately estimate completion dates due to complexity of the deals.</p><p> </p><p>The other part of the L&amp;P underspend was related to acquisitions resulting from the compensation schemes. The suite of schemes are demand led which means HS2 Ltd has very limited control over the timing of property purchases. Successful applicants to the schemes are allowed between one and three years after acceptance to decide on when they want their homes purchased.</p>","Harrogate and Knaresborough","Andrew Jones",,"2016-10-26T14:04:42.36Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/607564/answer","Biography information for Andrew Jones","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/607564/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/607564/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2016-10-21","High Speed Two","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, with reference to paragraph 2.2 of the High Speed Rail (Preparation) Act 2013 Expenditure Report, 1 April 2015 to 31 March 2016, published by his Department in October 2016, if he will detail the reasons, other than the delay in completing the acquisition of large-scale commercial properties, for the £192.7 million underspend referred to in that report.","false","Biography information for Dame Cheryl Gillan","Chesham and Amersham","Mrs Cheryl Gillan","49801"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/607565","Department for Transport","false","2016-10-26","<p>The process for putting in place traffic regulation orders (TROs) was identified as a major factor affecting the enforcement of pavement parking. The Department for Transport is therefore now considering how best to address the general improvement of the TRO-making process and will provide further information once this is available.</p><p> </p>","Harrogate and Knaresborough","Andrew Jones",,"2016-10-26T14:00:53.873Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/607565/answer","Biography information for Andrew Jones","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/607565/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/607565/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2016-10-21","Parking: Pedestrian Areas","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, pursuant to the Answer of 26 May 2016 to Question 37550, what further progress has been made on reviewing the legal and financial implications of an alternative pavement parking regime; and if he will make a statement.","false","Biography information for Royston Smith","Southampton, Itchen","Royston Smith","49804"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/607566","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2016-10-26","<p>We received a number of responses to questions 7 and 11 on the consultation CM8152, along with the other questions in the consultation, which the Government considered at the time. There was a range of views, comments and suggestions, from a range of stakeholders, relating to the proposition that local authorities should administer funding for supported housing and that supported housing should be removed from Housing Benefit altogether.</p>","Romsey and Southampton North","Caroline Nokes",,"2016-10-26T16:05:39.183Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/607566/answer","Biography information for Caroline Nokes","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/607566/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/607566/answer",,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2016-10-21","Housing Benefit: Supported Housing","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, pursuant to the Answer of 14 October 2016 to Question 47528 and the Answer of 17 October 2016 to HL 2020, if he will provide further detail on the consideration of responses to questions seven and 11 and summary paragraphs 45 and 67 of the consultation on housing benefit reform, Cm 8152, where there are references to meeting appointed housing needs through locally administered funding; and if he will make a statement.","false","Biography information for Tulip Siddiq","Hampstead and Kilburn","Tulip Siddiq","49803"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/607567","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2016-10-26","<p>The forecasted savings from the proposed changes to the Employment and Support Allowance work-related activity group from April 2017, can be found in Table 2.2 of the Budget 2016, available here:</p><p><a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/publications/budget-2016-documents/budget-2016" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/government/publications/budget-2016-documents/budget-2016</a></p><p>The 2015 Spending Review announced funding rising to at least £130 million a year by 2019/20 for the new Work and Health programme. The programme is one part of a wider offer of support for disabled people and our Work and Health Green Paper will be looking at how we can go even further.</p>","Portsmouth North","Penny Mordaunt",,"2016-10-26T10:30:08.17Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/607567/answer","Biography information for Penny Mordaunt","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/607567/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/607567/answer",,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2016-10-21","Employment and Support Allowance and Work and Health Programme","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, what he expects the savings to his Department to be of the proposed changes to the employment and support allowance work-related activity group; and how much funding has been allocated to the proposed work and health programme.","false","Biography information for Neil Gray","Airdrie and Shotts","Neil Gray","49760"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/607568","Department for International Trade","false","2016-11-01","<p>Following her appointment on 13 July 2016 the Prime Minister established the Department for International Trade (DIT). Until such time as a transfer of functions order establishes my Rt hon Friend the Secretary of State for International Trade as a corporation sole, DIT remains a unified Foreign and Commonwealth Office (FCO) and Department for Business, Energy &amp; Industrial Strategy (BEIS) department for accounting purposes. The transfer of functions order (No 2016/ 992) laid on 19 October 2016 will come into effect on 9 November 2016.</p><p>DIT is a new Department and is in the process of establishing a separate and distinct budget for its operating costs. This will be shared with Parliament through the Autumn Statement and Supplementary Estimates.</p>","Wyre Forest","Mark Garnier","49738","2016-11-01T13:05:10.2Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/607568/answer","Biography information for Mark Garnier","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/607568/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/607568/answer",,,,,"202","International Trade","International Trade","2016-10-21","Department for International Trade: Public Expenditure","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for International Trade, with reference to the Answer of 10 October 2016 to Question 46333, how much has been spent on the functions of the Department for International Trade; and what estimate he has made of how much will be spent on those functions by the end of the current fiscal year.","false","Biography information for Diana Johnson","Kingston upon Hull North","Diana Johnson","49739"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/607569","Department for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","false","2016-10-26","<p>The Department will provide a breakdown in the Annual Report and Accounts 2016-17.</p>","Stourbridge","Margot James",,"2016-10-26T15:26:39.697Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/607569/answer","Biography information for Margot James","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/607569/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/607569/answer",,,,,"201","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","2016-10-21","Department for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy: Costs","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy, pursuant to the Answer of 15 September 2016 to Question 45581, when his Department expects to be able to provide a breakdown of the costs incurred in the creation of his Department.","false","Biography information for Greg Mulholland","Leeds North West","Greg Mulholland","49773"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/607570","Department for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","false","2016-10-27","<p>My right hon. Friend the Secretary of State has received one letter from the hon. Member for Hartlepool (Iain Wright) as Chair of the Business, Innovation and Skills Committee and one letter from the hon. Member in his capacity as Chair of the British Pub Confederation. The Department has also received correspondence from members of the Pubs Advisory Service and the British Pub Confederation.</p>","Stourbridge","Margot James",,"2016-10-27T11:51:47.673Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/607570/answer","Biography information for Margot James","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/607570/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/607570/answer",,,,,"201","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","2016-10-21","Pubs Code Adjudicator","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy, what representations he has received on the ability of the Pubs Code Adjudicator to enact its role impartially.","false","Biography information for Greg Mulholland","Leeds North West","Greg Mulholland","49774"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/607571","Department for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","false","2016-10-31","<p>The office of the Pubs Code Adjudicator (PCA) will publish its complaints policy shortly. It will explain how the PCA will deal with any complaints about the behaviour or conduct of the Adjudicator or any member of the PCA team and how the PCA will ensure that every complaint is dealt with fairly and impartially.</p>","Stourbridge","Margot James",,"2016-10-31T14:10:12.033Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/607571/answer","Biography information for Margot James","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/607571/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/607571/answer",,,,,"201","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","2016-10-21","Pubs Code Adjudicator: Complaints","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy, what processes are in place to enable complaints about the Pubs Code Adjudicator to be submitted.","false","Biography information for Greg Mulholland","Leeds North West","Greg Mulholland","49775"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/607572","Department for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","false","2016-10-27","<p>The Pubs Code came into force 3 months ago, on 21 July 2016. It is therefore too early to have made an assessment of the compliance of pub-owning businesses with the Code.</p>","Stourbridge","Margot James",,"2016-10-27T11:52:31.207Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/607572/answer","Biography information for Margot James","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/607572/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/607572/answer",,,,,"201","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","2016-10-21","Public Houses","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy, what recent assessment he has made of the compliance of pub-owning businesses with the Pubs Code.","false","Biography information for Greg Mulholland","Leeds North West","Greg Mulholland","49769"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/607573","Department for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","false","2016-10-26","<p>A breakdown of transition costs will be provided in the Annual Report and Accounts 2016-17.</p>","Ruislip, Northwood and Pinner","Mr Nick Hurd",,"2016-10-26T13:34:44.577Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/607573/answer","Biography information for Mr Nick Hurd","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/607573/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/607573/answer",,,,,"201","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","2016-10-21","Department for Energy and Climate Change: Department for Business, Innovation and Skills","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy, what the expected cost is of the merger of the Department for Energy and Climate Change with the Department for Business, Innovation and Skills.","false","Biography information for Jack Dromey","Birmingham, Erdington","Jack Dromey","49802"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/607574","Department for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","false","2016-10-31","<p>The Department for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy, together with the Department for International Trade, works closely with offshore wind farm developers and UK supply chain companies to maximise the UK content in offshore wind farms.</p><p> </p><p>There is an agreed industry standard methodology in place for the Industry to measure and record the UK content in each offshore wind farm <a href="http://www.renewableuk.com/page/UKcontent" target="_blank">http://www.renewableuk.com/page/UKcontent</a>. The industry will publish anonymised and consolidated results to allow the sector and the public to track the sector’s progress towards fulfilling their vision. As such, the Government does not comment on the construction phases of individual developers.</p><p> </p>","Hereford and South Herefordshire","Jesse Norman","49788","2016-10-31T15:39:59.763Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/607574/answer","Biography information for Jesse Norman","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/607574/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/607574/answer",,,,,"201","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","2016-10-21","Wind Power: Seas and Oceans","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy, what plans the Government has to (a) monitor and (b) assess the level of UK content during the construction phase of (i) Hywind, (ii) Galloper, (iii) Dudgeon, (iv) Race Bank, (v) Burbo Bank Extension, (vi) Walney Extension, (vii) Beatrice, (viii) Rampion, (ix) Aberdeen Bay and (x) Blyth Offshore Demonstrator wind farms.","false","Biography information for Jenny Chapman","Darlington","Jenny Chapman","49789"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/607575","Department for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","false","2016-10-31","<p>The Department for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy, together with the Department for International Trade, works closely with offshore wind farm developers and UK supply chain companies to maximise the UK content in offshore wind farms.</p><p> </p><p>There is an agreed industry standard methodology in place for the Industry to measure and record the UK content in each offshore wind farm <a href="http://www.renewableuk.com/page/UKcontent" target="_blank">http://www.renewableuk.com/page/UKcontent</a>. The industry will publish anonymised and consolidated results to allow the sector and the public to track the sector’s progress towards fulfilling their vision. As such, the Government does not comment on the construction phases of individual developers.</p><p> </p>","Hereford and South Herefordshire","Jesse Norman","49789","2016-10-31T15:39:59.683Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/607575/answer","Biography information for Jesse Norman","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/607575/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/607575/answer",,,,,"201","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","2016-10-21","Wind Power: Seas and Oceans","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy, how his Department (a) assesses and (b) monitors the level of UK content during the construction phase of off-shore wind farm developments.","false","Biography information for Jenny Chapman","Darlington","Jenny Chapman","49788"
