rces/606818/answer","Biography information for Mr Robert Goodwill","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/606818/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/606818/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2016-10-20","Refugees: Calais","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, which local authorities have agreed to relocate refugees from the camp in Calais.","false","Biography information for Sir Hugo Swire","East Devon","Sir Hugo Swire","49677"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/606819","Home Office","false","2016-11-01","<p>Potential victims of modern slavery in England and Wales are supported through a Government-funded contract, delivered by the Salvation Army. This provides extremely vulnerable victims with a tailored and specialised package of care and support. This can include accommodation in a shelter.</p>","Truro and Falmouth","Sarah Newton",,"2016-11-01T14:09:42.487Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/606819/answer","Biography information for Sarah Newton","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/606819/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/606819/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2016-10-20","Asylum: Human Trafficking","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, how many asylum seekers who are also either identified or potential victims of trafficking were housed in safe house accommodation rather than National Asylum Support Service accommodation in 2015.","false","Biography information for Fiona Mactaggart","Slough","Fiona Mactaggart","49648"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/606820","Home Office","false","2016-11-01","<p>Dealing with unauthorised traveller sites requires a multi-agency response, involving local authorities and supported by the police.</p><p>The police have powers under the Criminal Justice and Public Order Act 1994 to remove travellers from a site. The decision on whether to use these powers is an operational matter for the police who must consider their duties under the Equalities Act and Human Rights Act in each case.</p>","Great Yarmouth","Brandon Lewis",,"2016-11-01T16:24:31.573Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/606820/answer","Biography information for Brandon Lewis","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/606820/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/606820/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2016-10-20","Travellers: Caravan Sites","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, what assessment her Department has made of the reasons for police forces across (a) regions and (b) the UK having variations in their respective plans of action for dealing with traveller camps in (i) public parks and recreation sites and (ii) other publicly-owned land.","false","Biography information for Steve McCabe","Birmingham, Selly Oak","Steve McCabe","49635"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/606821","Home Office","false","2016-10-31","<p>Although the decision to clear the camp in Calais is a matter for the French Government, the UK and France remain committed to working together to protect our shared border in Calais and address the humanitarian challenges in the camps.</p><p>Both governments are clear that those in northern France in need of protection should claim asylum in France and those not in need should return to their home country.</p><p>Our priority is to ensure the safety and security of children in the camps. The UK Government has made clear its commitment to transfer unaccompanied refugee children under the 2016 Immigration Act, where it is in their best interests, and to ensure those with close family in the UK are brought here using the Dublin Regulation.</p>","Scarborough and Whitby","Mr Robert Goodwill",,"2016-10-31T17:56:00.407Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/606821/answer","Biography information for Mr Robert Goodwill","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/606821/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/606821/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2016-10-20","Migrant Camps: Calais","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, what assessment she has made of the effect on the UK's obligations as agreed in the August 2015 joint ministerial declarations, Managing migratory flows in Calais, of the French government's decision to close the Calais camp for refugees and migrants.","false","Biography information for Diana Johnson","Kingston upon Hull North","Diana Johnson","49621"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/606822","Home Office","false","2016-10-31","<p>The Home Office does not hold the information requested.</p>","Great Yarmouth","Brandon Lewis",,"2016-10-31T16:44:13.957Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/606822/answer","Biography information for Brandon Lewis","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/606822/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/606822/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2016-10-20","Criminal Records: EU Countries","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, how many times (a) have EU member states notified the UK and (b) has the UK notified other EU member states of convictions of nationals of their respective countries via the European Criminal Records Information system in each year since 2012.","false","Biography information for Diana Johnson","Kingston upon Hull North","Diana Johnson","49622"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/606823","Home Office","false","2016-11-01","<p>Where an employer is considering an individual’s suitability for employment it is the employer’s responsibility to ensure the individual is suitable to work with vulnerable people (including children). This may include seeking information from other countries, including EU member states. The Disclosure and Barring Service uses information from the England &amp; Wales, Northern Ireland and Scottish barred lists.</p>","Truro and Falmouth","Sarah Newton",,"2016-11-01T16:26:03.597Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/606823/answer","Biography information for Sarah Newton","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/606823/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/606823/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2016-10-20","Vetting: EU Nationals","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, on how many occasions have (a) EU member states exchanged with the UK and (b) the UK exchanged with other EU member states information related to EU citizens on the (i) adults and (ii) children's barred lists in each year since 2012.","false","Biography information for Diana Johnson","Kingston upon Hull North","Diana Johnson","49623"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/606824","Home Office","false","2016-11-03","<p>The Disclosure and Barring Service does not collect this specific information.</p>","Truro and Falmouth","Sarah Newton",,"2016-11-03T17:52:03.607Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/606824/answer","Biography information for Sarah Newton","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/606824/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/606824/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2016-10-20","Vetting: EU Nationals","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, how many EU nationals are recorded by the Disclosure and Barring Service as having worked in regulated activity for (a) children and (b) adults in each year since 2012.","false","Biography information for Diana Johnson","Kingston upon Hull North","Diana Johnson","49620"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/606825","Department for Communities and Local Government","false","2016-10-25","<p>Business rates are based on valuations from the Valuation Office Agency and we do not intervene in their independent assessments. We have proposed a £3.4 billion transitional relief scheme to ensure that no ratepayer is unfairly penalised by the 2017 revaluation.</p>","Nuneaton","Mr Marcus Jones",,"2016-10-25T16:26:12.523Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/606825/answer","Biography information for Mr Marcus Jones","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/606825/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/606825/answer",,,,,"7","Communities and Local Government","Communities and Local Government","2016-10-20","Solar Power: Non-domestic Rates","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Communities and Local Government, what assessment he has made of the effect on the solar power industry of the proposed 2017 business rate rise for organisations investing in rooftop solar power for their own consumption.","false","Biography information for Mr Ben Bradshaw","Exeter","Mr Ben Bradshaw","49734"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/606826","Home Office","false","2016-10-25","<p>The number of fixed penalty notices (FPNs) issued to motorists for the use of handheld mobile phones while driving in each of the years from 2010 to 2014 is published in the annual “Police Powers and Procedures” statistical bulletin, which can be found at <a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/collections/police-powers-and-procedures-england-and-wales" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/government/collections/police-powers-and-procedures-england-and-wales</a></p>","Great Yarmouth","Brandon Lewis",,"2016-10-25T16:15:08.153Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/606826/answer","Biography information for Brandon Lewis","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/606826/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/606826/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2016-10-20","Road Traffic Offences: Mobile phones","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, how many fixed penalty notices were issued by the police to motorists who use mobile telephones while driving in the last five years for which figures are available; and if she will make a statement.","false","Biography information for Mr Ben Bradshaw","Exeter","Mr Ben Bradshaw","49735"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/606827","Home Office","false","2016-10-31","<p>Home Office teams have been deployed to France to work with the French Authorities to speed up the identification and transfer of eligible cases under both the Dublin Regulation and Section 67 of the Immigration Act 2016.</p><p>More children are arriving to join their family in the UK each day. It is therefore not possible to provide an exact number of outstanding family reunion applications.</p><p>The UK has made clear that the remaining children, including those who do not qualify for family reunion must be looked after in safe facilities. The UK Government is ready to help fund such facilities and provide resources to aid the decision-making.</p>","Scarborough and Whitby","Mr Robert Goodwill",,"2016-10-31T17:28:32.487Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/606827/answer","Biography information for Mr Robert Goodwill","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/606827/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/606827/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2016-10-20","Refugees: Children","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, with reference to the Answer of 22 September 2016 to Question HL1788, how many outstanding family reunion applications there are for unaccompanied children from France; what steps are being taken to ensure those applications are processed quickly; and what steps she is taking to ensure that the UK remains in contact with children with outstanding applications in the event that they are moved away from Calais.","false","Biography information for Diana Johnson","Kingston upon Hull North","Diana Johnson","49716"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/606828","Home Office","false","2016-10-31","<p>The Government will process cases in line with the EU’s Dublin Regulation and Section 67 of the Immigration Act 2016.</p><p>The Dublin Regulation does not confer leave on individuals; it is a mechanism for transferring responsibility of asylum claims between Member States.</p>","Scarborough and Whitby","Mr Robert Goodwill",,"2016-10-31T16:50:39.733Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/606828/answer","Biography information for Mr Robert Goodwill","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/606828/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/606828/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2016-10-20","Refugees: Calais","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, if the Government will grant all children brought from Calais under the Dublin agreement or the Dubs amendment indefinite leave to remain.","false","Biography information for Tom Brake","Carshalton and Wallington","Tom Brake","49715"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/606829","Home Office","false","2016-10-25","<p>The EU’s Dublin Regulation clearly sets out the criteria for transferring asylum claims between Member States. The Government wishes to reaffirm that migrants in Calais have not yet been determined as refugees, and furthermore, the Dublin Regulation is the EU’s mechanism for transferring asylum claims, rather than a resettlement route. Section 67 of the Immigration Act sets out that ‘unaccompanied refugee children’ will be relocated to the UK. In respect of Calais, the Government has been clear that unaccompanied children will be prioritised if they meet the Dublin criteria.</p><p>We work closely with the French authorities and their partner agencies to ensure all those who come to the UK from the camps in Calais are eligible under the Dublin Regulation. All individuals are referred to the UK authorities by the NGO France Terre D'asile (FTDA) and are then interviewed by French and UK officials. Basic security checks are conducted on all individuals prior to arrival, with further verification carried out once in the UK.</p><p>Where credible and clear documentary evidence of age is not available, criteria including physical appearance and demeanour are used as part of the interview process to assess age. Where we believe someone is significantly over 18, they will be refused. The Home Office does not use dental x-rays to confirm the ages of those seeking asylum as they have been described by the British Dental Association as inaccurate, inappropriate and unethical.</p><p>Since June the Home Office has been working closely with local authorities and Strategic Migration Partnerships across the UK to ensure that we have the structures in place to support the transfer of unaccompanied asylum seeking and refugee children, both within the UK and from Europe.</p>","Scarborough and Whitby","Mr Robert Goodwill","49676 ; 49677 ; 49695","2016-10-25T12:25:04.8Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/606829/answer","Biography information for Mr Robert Goodwill","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/606829/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/606829/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2016-10-20","Refugees: Calais","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, what assessment she has made of the age of young refugees from the camp in Calais received into the UK.","false","Biography information for Sir Hugo Swire","East Devon","Sir Hugo Swire","49694"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/606830","Home Office","false","2016-10-25","<p>The EU’s Dublin Regulation clearly sets out the criteria for transferring asylum claims between Member States. The Government wishes to reaffirm that migrants in Calais have not yet been determined as refugees, and furthermore, the Dublin Regulation is the EU’s mechanism for transferring asylum claims, rather than a resettlement route. Section 67 of the Immigration Act sets out that ‘unaccompanied refugee children’ will be relocated to the UK. In respect of Calais, the Government has been clear that unaccompanied children will be prioritised if they meet the Dublin criteria.</p><p>We work closely with the French authorities and their partner agencies to ensure all those who come to the UK from the camps in Calais are eligible under the Dublin Regulation. All individuals are referred to the UK authorities by the NGO France Terre D'asile (FTDA) and are then interviewed by French and UK officials. Basic security checks are conducted on all individuals prior to arrival, with further verification carried out once in the UK.</p><p>Where credible and clear documentary evidence of age is not available, criteria including physical appearance and demeanour are used as part of the interview process to assess age. Where we believe someone is significantly over 18, they will be refused. The Home Office does not use dental x-rays to confirm the ages of those seeking asylum as they have been described by the British Dental Association as inaccurate, inappropriate and unethical.</p><p>Since June the Home Office has been working closely with local authorities and Strategic Migration Partnerships across the UK to ensure that we have the structures in place to support the transfer of unaccompanied asylum seeking and refugee children, both within the UK and from Europe.</p>","Scarborough and Whitby","Mr Robert Goodwill","49676 ; 49677 ; 49694","2016-10-25T12:25:05.927Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/606830/answer","Biography information for Mr Robert Goodwill","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/606830/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/606830/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2016-10-20","Refugees: Calais","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, what steps she is taking to pre-screen young refugees from the camp in Calais before they enter the UK.","false","Biography information for Sir Hugo Swire","East Devon","Sir Hugo Swire","49695"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/606831","Home Office","false","2016-10-31","<p>Work continues with local authorities and International Partners to deliver the Government’s commitment to resettle 20,000 Syrian refugees over the lifetime of this Parliament and we are on track to do this.</p><p>Progress on resettlement will be indicated in quarterly immigration statistics. The last set of statistics, published on 25 August 2016 showed that 2,646 Syrians were relocated to the UK under the Syrian Vulnerable Persons Resettlement scheme between October 2015 and June 2016.</p>","Scarborough and Whitby","Mr Robert Goodwill",,"2016-10-31T17:14:24.637Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/606831/answer","Biography information for Mr Robert Goodwill","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/606831/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/606831/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2016-10-20","Refugees: Syria","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, pursuant to the Answer of 10 October 2016 to Question 46417, what assessment the Government has made of the likelihood of reaching its target of resettling 20,000 Syrians before the end of the current Parliament at current resettlement rates.","false","Biography information for Mr Roger Godsiff","Birmingham, Hall Green","Mr Roger Godsiff","49683"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/606832","Home Office","false","2016-12-21","<p>Our records indicate that since 2010, 1,003 confirmed victims of trafficking have been granted refugee status or other form of protection as a result of an application for asylum. It is not possible to say whether refugee status was awarded due to the applicant being a victim of trafficking without a review of individual case record at disproportionate cost.</p>","Scarborough and Whitby","Mr Robert Goodwill",,"2016-12-21T10:21:06.143Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/606832/answer","Biography information for Mr Robert Goodwill","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/606832/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/606832/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2016-10-20","Refugees: Human Trafficking","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, how many people have been granted refugee status or another type of subsidiary protection in the UK on the basis that they have been trafficked since 2010.","false","Biography information for Fiona Mactaggart","Slough","Fiona Mactaggart","49684"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/606833","Department for International Development","false","2016-10-26","<p>Many DFID programmes reach and include older people, supporting their needs and rights. These include programmes to strengthen health systems and eye care, and specific programmes for the poorest including supporting slum dwellers in Tanzania and supporting widows resulting from the Genocide in Rwanda. Ageing features in DFID country level poverty analyses as a key factor in understanding poverty. In addition DFID is taking a global leadership role to achieve better quality and use of age disaggregated data to ensure that the Sustainable Development Goals leave no one behind. DFID’s Inclusive Societies Department in Policy Division holds policy responsibility for ageing.</p>","Penrith and The Border","Rory Stewart",,"2016-10-26T16:28:51.663Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/606833/answer","Biography information for Rory Stewart","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/606833/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/606833/answer",,,,,"20","International Development","International Development","2016-10-20","Developing Countries: Older People","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for International Development, what steps her Department is taking to support the needs and rights of older people in developing countries; and whether ageing will be reinstated as a responsibility under her Department's Inclusive Societies policy.","false","Biography information for Patrick Grady","Glasgow North","Patrick Grady","49681"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/606834","Department for International Development","false","2016-10-26","<p>The UK has been one of the earliest and largest donors to the UN’s Mosul Flash Appeal, focused on preparing for the humanitarian consequences of Mosul military operations. This includes £40 million announced by my right Hon. Friend, the Secretary of State for International Development, at the UN General Assembly in September. With this, our partners will provide assistance, including shelter and support kits for 66,000 people, comprising vital equipment for any displaced family, such as blankets, plastic sheets, buckets and other containers for water, cooking items and soap. It will also provide emergency healthcare for 42,000 people, through four mobile medical teams, upgraded emergency medical surgeries, three ambulances and two health facilities with equipment, medication and light rehabilitation.</p><p>This brings the UK’s total humanitarian commitment to £90 million in 2016, and £169.5 million since summer 2014.</p>","Penrith and The Border","Rory Stewart",,"2016-10-26T16:30:16.023Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/606834/answer","Biography information for Rory Stewart","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/606834/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/606834/answer",,,,,"20","International Development","International Development","2016-10-20","Iraq: Armed Conflict","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for International Development, what (a) material and (b) humanitarian assistance the Government is providing to assist civilians fleeing the city of Mosul; and if she will make a statement.","false","Biography information for Mr Jim Cunningham","Coventry South","Mr Jim Cunningham","49706"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/606835","Department for International Development","false","2016-10-27","<p>In addition to the £5m of support to help thousands of people affected by Hurricane Matthew in Haiti, DFID announced a further £3m on 16 October to strengthen the response to cholera and wider health concerns. The UK has provided a total of more than £46m to Haiti since 2010, which has included support to Haiti's health sector. The priority now is to reach those affected by Hurricane Matthew and provide them with water, sanitation, healthcare and shelter. DFID is leading, with other key donors, on lobbying for an improved response to the hurricane, and is working to meet the needs of the most affected. DFID continues to provide support, including to the country's health infrastructure, through multilateral contributions to UN agencies, the World Bank, the EU and other international institutions.</p>","Penrith and The Border","Rory Stewart",,"2016-10-27T14:52:30.907Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/606835/answer","Biography information for Rory Stewart","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/606835/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/606835/answer",,,,,"20","International Development","International Development","2016-10-20","Haiti: Hurricanes and Tornadoes","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for International Development, pursuant to the Answer of 14 October 2016 to Question 47281, if her Department will allocate funds to long-term projects in Haiti to address the lack of health infrastructure in that country caused by Hurricane Matthew.","false","Biography information for Catherine West","Hornsey and Wood Green","Catherine West","49608"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/606836","Department for International Development","false","2016-10-26","<p>Preventing deforestation is a key priority for the UK. More than one billion people depend on forests for their livelihoods, and forests are vital resources which support economic growth in developing countries. At the Paris climate change conference in 2015, the UK Germany and Norway collectively committed to providing up to US$1 billion per year by 2020, or over $5 billion in the period 2015-20, to prevent deforestation and ensure that forests are managed sustainably.</p>","Stockton South","James Wharton",,"2016-10-26T16:22:45.137Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/606836/answer","Biography information for James Wharton","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/606836/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/606836/answer",,,,,"20","International Development","International Development","2016-10-20","Developing Countries: Forests","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for International Development, whether the Government plans to maintain funding to prevent deforestation in developing countries; and whether the UK provides any funding to help prevent large-scale forest fires in developing countries.","false","Biography information for Mr Roger Godsiff","Birmingham, Hall Green","Mr Roger Godsiff","49674"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/606837","Ministry of Justice","false","2016-10-28","<p>Information on the number of people who have lost more than 25 per cent of their financial claims compensation to the claims management company (CMC) handling their claim is not held centrally.</p><p> </p><p>Our priority is to protect consumers who choose to use CMCs. We have consulted on proposals to cap the level of fees that CMCs providing financial claims services can charge consumers. These proposals aim to help consumers get more of the compensation due to them. We are carefully considering the consultation responses and the Government will publish its response in due course.</p>","North East Hertfordshire","Sir Oliver Heald","49679 ; 49688","2016-10-28T11:39:45.897Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/606837/answer","Biography information for Sir Oliver Heald","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/606837/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/606837/answer",,,,,"54","Justice","Justice","2016-10-20","Claims Management Services","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Justice, what information her Department holds on the number of people who have paid more than 25 per cent of their financial claims compensation to the claims management company handling their claim in each of the last three years; and what steps her Department is taking to prevent those companies from taking commission of more than 24 per cent.","false","Biography information for Ian Austin","Dudley North","Ian Austin","49678"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/606838","Ministry of Justice","false","2016-10-28","<p>Details of all ministerial meetings with external companies are published on gov.uk. Information on officials’ meetings is not held centrally.</p><p> </p><p>We remain vigilant to all incidents involving drones and take the threat they pose to prison security very seriously. We have already introduced new legislation to further strengthen our powers, so that anyone found using a drone in an attempt to get contraband into prisons can be punished with a sentence of up to two years imprisonment. We take a zero tolerance approach to smuggling of contraband into prisons and work closely with the police and Crown Prosecution Service to ensure those caught are prosecuted.</p><p> </p><p>A range of methods to counter the threat posed by drones are continuously being trialled and evaluated for their effectiveness across the prison estate.</p>","East Surrey","Mr Sam Gyimah",,"2016-10-28T13:57:55.7Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/606838/answer","Biography information for Mr Sam Gyimah","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/606838/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/606838/answer",,,,,"54","Justice","Justice","2016-10-20","Unmanned Air Vehicles","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Justice, how many meetings (a) Ministers of her Department and (b) officials of HM Prison Service have had with drone manufacturers in each quarter of each of the last five years; and if she will make a statement.","false","Biography information for Richard Burden","Birmingham, Northfield","Richard Burden","49618"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/606839","Ministry of Justice","false","2016-10-28","<p>The review is making good progress and I expect to announce its conclusions in due course.</p>","North East Hertfordshire","Sir Oliver Heald",,"2016-10-28T12:08:08.953Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/606839/answer","Biography information for Sir Oliver Heald","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/606839/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/606839/answer",,,,,"54","Justice","Justice","2016-10-20","Employment Tribunals Service: Fees and Charges","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Justice, with reference to the Answer of 19 January 2016 to Question 21876, what progress her Department has made on its review of the effect of the introduction of tribunal fees; and if she will issue a fixed date for the publication of that review.","false","Biography information for Dawn Butler","Brent Central","Dawn Butler","49615"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/606840","Ministry of Justice","false","2016-10-28","<p>Information on the number of people who have lost more than 25 per cent of their financial claims compensation to the claims management company (CMC) handling their claim is not held centrally.</p><p> </p><p>Our priority is to protect consumers who choose to use CMCs. We have consulted on proposals to cap the level of fees that CMCs providing financial claims services can charge consumers. These proposals aim to help consumers get more of the compensation due to them. We are carefully considering the consultation responses and the Government will publish its response in due course.</p>","North East Hertfordshire","Sir Oliver Heald","49678 ; 49679","2016-10-28T11:39:46.02Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/606840/answer","Biography information for Sir Oliver Heald","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/606840/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/606840/answer",,,,,"54","Justice","Justice","2016-10-20","Claims Management Services","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Justice, when the Government plans to publish the outcome of its consultation on capping the fees charged to consumers by claims management companies.","false","Biography information for Ian Austin","Dudley North","Ian Austin","49688"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/606841","Ministry of Justice","false","2016-10-28","<p>The Secretary of State is the minister responsible for claims management regulation.</p>","North East Hertfordshire","Sir Oliver Heald",,"2016-10-28T11:46:30.217Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/606841/answer","Biography information for Sir Oliver Heald","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/606841/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/606841/answer",,,,,"54","Justice","Justice","2016-10-20","Ministry of Justice: Claims Management Services","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Justice, which Minister of her Department has responsibility for claims management company regulation.","false","Biography information for Ian Austin","Dudley North","Ian Austin","49705"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/606842","Ministry of Justice","false","2016-10-28","<p>Information on the number of people who have lost more than 25 per cent of their financial claims compensation to the claims management company (CMC) handling their claim is not held centrally.</p><p> </p><p>Our priority is to protect consumers who choose to use CMCs. We have consulted on proposals to cap the level of fees that CMCs providing financial claims services can charge consumers. These proposals aim to help consumers get more of the compensation due to them. We are carefully considering the consultation responses and the Government will publish its response in due course.</p>","North East Hertfordshire","Sir Oliver Heald","49678 ; 49688","2016-10-28T11:39:45.96Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/606842/answer","Biography information for Sir Oliver Heald","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/606842/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/606842/answer",,,,,"54","Justice","Justice","2016-10-20","Claims Management Services","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Justice, what progress her Department has made on reducing costs for consumers in making financial claims.","false","Biography information for Ian Austin","Dudley North","Ian Austin","49679"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/606843","Department for Transport","false","2016-10-26","<p>Since 2000, development consent has been given for ten Strategic Rail Freight Interchanges across Great Britain. The Department for Transport does not monitor progress in constructing these sites. However we understand that not all of these interchanges have yet been constructed.</p>","Blackpool North and Cleveleys","Paul Maynard",,"2016-10-26T15:30:46.007Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/606843/answer","Biography information for Paul Maynard","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/606843/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/606843/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2016-10-20","Railways: Freight","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, how many strategic rail freight interchanges have been granted planning permission since 2000; and of those granted permission how many have been built.","false","Biography information for Mrs Anne Main","St Albans","Mrs Anne Main","49719"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/606844","Department for Transport","false","2016-10-26","<p>The hybrid Bill for HS2 Phase One is proceeding through Parliament and we are aiming to achieve Royal Assent by the end of 2016, with construction starting in 2017 and the first trains running by the end of 2026.</p><p> </p>","Harrogate and Knaresborough","Andrew Jones",,"2016-10-26T15:21:37.56Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/606844/answer","Biography information for Andrew Jones","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/606844/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/606844/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2016-10-20","High Speed 2 Railway Line","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, what recent estimate he has made of the date that the first phase of High Speed 2 will be completed and open to the public.","false","Biography information for Grant Shapps","Welwyn Hatfield","Grant Shapps","49687"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/606845","Department for Transport","false","2016-10-25","<p>Due to existing diary commitments, it is unlikely that I, as the Roads Minister, will be able to visit the A595 in Copeland before Christmas 2016. Nevertheless, it is my intention to visit roads across the country over the coming months.</p>","South Holland and The Deepings","Mr John Hayes",,"2016-10-25T08:22:35.323Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/606845/answer","Biography information for Sir John Hayes","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/606845/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/606845/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2016-10-20","A595","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, pursuant to the Answer of 20 October 2016 to Question 48986, if he will visit the A595 in Copeland before Christmas 2016.","false","Biography information for Mr Jamie Reed","Copeland","Mr Jamie Reed","49704"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/606846","Department for Transport","false","2016-10-26","<p>The UK has 16 intermodal rail freight interchanges. These are:</p><p> </p><p>o Birmingham International Railfreight Terminal</p><p>o Daventry International Railfreight Terminal</p><p>o Hams Hall</p><p>o Widnes</p><p>o Wentloog</p><p>o Selby</p><p>o Doncaster Railport</p><p>o Grangemouth</p><p>o Trafford Park Euroterminal</p><p>o Trafford Park</p><p>o Lawley Street</p><p>o Leeds – Freightliner</p><p>o Mossend Euroterminal</p><p>o Wakefield Euroterminal</p><p>o Willesden Euroterminal</p><ul><li>Barking</li></ul><p> </p><p> </p><p>In addition to these interchanges, there are a large number of port-located rail terminals and small independent facilities nationwide.</p><p> </p><p>The usage and available capacity of these terminals varies by facility and time of year. However, overall changes in the rail freight market means there has been an increase, in recent years, in imports and exports of containerised goods through the major ports (intermodal freight), increasing utilisation at these sites.</p><p> </p>","Blackpool North and Cleveleys","Paul Maynard",,"2016-10-26T15:34:48.863Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/606846/answer","Biography information for Paul Maynard","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/606846/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/606846/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2016-10-20","Railways: Freight","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, how many rail freight interchanges there are in the UK; and what the utilisation rate is on the freight network.","false","Biography information for Mrs Anne Main","St Albans","Mrs Anne Main","49714"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/606847","Department for Transport","false","2016-10-25","<p>I recently announced a new contract for the Cross Country rail franchise that will run until October 2019. This franchise offers a number of passenger experience improvements such as free wi-fi on trains. The franchise retains the same level of service between Birmingham and Stansted Airport. I am aware that there are aspirations for improvements in the Cross Country service through Peterborough. Currently, there are no suitable diesel trains available to allow this to happen. However, should this position change, we would work with Cross Country to consider what services enhancements may be possible to deliver. There may be further enhancements across the Cross Country network, once it’s competitively let in 2019.</p>","Blackpool North and Cleveleys","Paul Maynard",,"2016-10-25T14:48:31.927Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/606847/answer","Biography information for Paul Maynard","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/606847/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/606847/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2016-10-20","Cross Country Trains","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, what steps he is taking to improve (a) rail connectivity and (b) service delivery on Cross Country Trains which run between Birmingham and Stansted and through Peterborough in the next Control Period; and if he will make a statement.","false","Biography information for Mr Stewart Jackson","Peterborough","Mr Stewart Jackson","49637"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/606848","Department for Transport","false","2016-10-27","<p>We are spending more than £600 million by 2020 to support the development, manufacture and use of ultra low emission vehicles. This programme includes incentives to encourage motorists to choose cleaner vehicles, and grants for essential recharging infrastructure. This is putting the UK on track to meet our goal of all new cars and vans being zero emission by 2040, making almost all cars and vans zero emission by 2050.</p>","South Holland and The Deepings","Mr John Hayes",,"2016-10-27T11:00:51.66Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/606848/answer","Biography information for Sir John Hayes","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/606848/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/606848/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2016-10-20","Engines","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, if he will make it his Department's policy to ban internal combustion engines by 2030 to promote zero emission mobility.","false","Biography information for Richard Burden","Birmingham, Northfield","Richard Burden","49641"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/606849","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2016-10-26","<p>Statistics on Employment and Support Allowance off-flows, by phase of claim, are published and available at:</p><p><a href="http://tabulation-tool.dwp.gov.uk/flows/flows_off/tabtool.html" target="_blank">http://tabulation-tool.dwp.gov.uk/flows/flows_off/tabtool.html</a></p><p>Guidance on how to extract the information can be found at:</p><p><a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/publications/dwp-tabulation-tool-guidance" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/government/publications/dwp-tabulation-tool-guidance</a></p><p>The information requested on Employment and Support Allowance claimants reclaiming ESA and the proportion of claimants who had fluctuating illnesses is not readily available and to provide it would incur disproportionate cost.</p>","Portsmouth North","Penny Mordaunt",,"2016-10-26T14:06:25.72Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/606849/answer","Biography information for Penny Mordaunt","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/606849/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/606849/answer",,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2016-10-20","Employment and Support Allowance","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, how many employment support allowance claimants in the work-related activity group have (a) come off that allowance and (b) had periods of reclaiming that allowance and what proportion of those claimants had fluctuating illnesses in the latest period for which figures are available.","false","Biography information for Neil Gray","Airdrie and Shotts","Neil Gray","49654"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/606850","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2016-10-26","<p>A number of representations were received regarding removal of the work-related activity component for new employment and support allowance claimants only. We do not hold a central record of this information.</p>","Portsmouth North","Penny Mordaunt",,"2016-10-26T15:14:42.88Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/606850/answer","Biography information for Penny Mordaunt","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/606850/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/606850/answer",,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2016-10-20","Employment and Support Allowance","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, how many representations he has received (a) in favour and (b) against reductions in the employment support allowance for people in the work-related activity group.","false","Biography information for Neil Gray","Airdrie and Shotts","Neil Gray","49653"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/606851","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2016-10-26","<p>The information is provided in the table below.</p><p> </p><p><strong>Estimated breakdown of households affected by the lower cap levels by benefit receipt, 2016/17, GB</strong></p><table><tbody><tr><td rowspan="2"><p><strong>Benefit Received</strong></p></td><td colspan="2"><p><strong>Proportion of Capped Households</strong></p></td></tr><tr><td><p>London Borough of Tower Hamlets</p></td><td><p>London</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>Employment and Support Allowance</p></td><td><p>25%</p></td><td><p>22%</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>Income Support</p></td><td><p>36%</p></td><td><p>39%</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>Jobseeker's Allowance</p></td><td><p>27%</p></td><td><p>25%</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>Other</p></td><td><p>12%</p></td><td><p>14%</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>Total</p></td><td><p>100%</p></td><td><p>100%</p></td></tr></tbody></table><p> </p><p>Notes:</p><ol><li>Figures may not sum due to rounding.</li><li>London is defined as the 32 boroughs of London and the City of London.</li><li>Estimates assume no behavioural responses - any behavioural responses to the lower cap, such as claimants moving into employment, would cause the number of households affected to reduce and may change the proportional split.</li><li>The methodology used to estimate the households affected by the cap is consistent with that described in the latest impact assessment published here: <a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/publications/welfare-reform-and-work-act-impact-assessment-for-the-benefit-cap" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/government/publications/welfare-reform-and-work-act-impact-assessment-for-the-benefit-cap</a></li></ol>","Romsey and Southampton North","Caroline Nokes",,"2016-10-26T14:48:04.553Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/606851/answer","Biography information for Caroline Nokes","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/606851/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/606851/answer",,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2016-10-20","Social Security Benefits: Greater London","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, pursuant to the Answer of 6 September 2016 to Question 45327, what proportion of claimants affected by the lower benefit cap in (a) Tower Hamlets and (b) London are in receipt of (i) jobseeker's allowance, (ii) employment support allowance and (iii) income support.","false","Biography information for Jim Fitzpatrick","Poplar and Limehouse","Jim Fitzpatrick","49609"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/606852","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2016-10-28","<p>A number of international studies, and a 2005 report<sup><sup>[1]</sup></sup> by the Organisation for Economic Co-operation and Development argued that “financial incentives to work can be improved by either cutting welfare benefit levels, or introducing in-work benefits while leaving benefit levels unchanged”.</p><p>There will be new funding worth £60 million in 2017/18, rising to £100 million in 2020/21, which will support those with limited capability for work to move towards and into suitable employment. We will also soon publish a Green Paper that will explore a range of options for long-term reform across different sectors, targeting the factors which contribute to the Disability Employment Gap.</p><p>[1] <a href="http://www.oecd.org/employment/emp/36780865.pdf" target="_blank">http://www.oecd.org/employment/emp/36780865.pdf</a></p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p>","Portsmouth North","Penny Mordaunt",,"2016-10-28T11:48:08.76Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/606852/answer","Biography information for Penny Mordaunt","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/606852/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/606852/answer",,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2016-10-20","Employment and Support Allowance","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, if he will publish the evidence his Department has received which illustrates that a change in the level of employment and support allowance work-related activity group funding will support claimants into work.","false","Biography information for Neil Gray","Airdrie and Shotts","Neil Gray","49724"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/606853","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2016-10-26","<p>If an employment and support allowance claimant appeals following mandatory reconsideration, benefit can be paid at the assessment phase rate pending the appeal hearing. Following a successful appeal the payment will be backdated to cover the period of mandatory reconsideration, provided medical evidence is supplied.</p>","Portsmouth North","Penny Mordaunt",,"2016-10-26T15:43:47.523Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/606853/answer","Biography information for Penny Mordaunt","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/606853/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/606853/answer",,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2016-10-20","Employment and Support Allowance: Appeals","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, what provision is in place to support employment and support allowance (ESA) claimants after a successful ESA appeal during the interim period before the reinstatement of that benefit and payment of arrears.","false","Biography information for Deidre Brock","Edinburgh North and Leith","Deidre  Brock","49707"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/606854","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2016-10-27","<p>I am responding on behalf of the Secretary of State (SoS), as Minister for Pensions with overall responsibility on this issue.</p><p>The previous Minister Baroness Altmann and Minister Shailesh Vara (the previous Under-Secretary of State for DWP) met with representatives of the WASPI group on 29th June 2016 to listen to their concerns. Although WASPI’s ask was unclear, at the time, Ministers indicated that the DWP did not have the available funds to deliver further concessions.</p><p>One other outcome from that meeting was that WASPI agreed to explore options with the relevant All Party Parliamentary Group (APPG). A meeting between APPG representatives, the SoS and myself is being taken forward, and consequently there is nothing further to be gained from meeting WASPI representatives directly.</p><p>I should add that I have been quite clear that the Government will make no further changes to the pension age or pay financial redress in lieu of a pension.</p>","Watford","Richard Harrington",,"2016-10-27T14:45:15.303Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/606854/answer","Biography information for Richard Harrington","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/606854/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/606854/answer",,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2016-10-20","State Retirement Pensions: Females","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, if he will meet representatives of the Women Against State Pension Inequality campaign.","false","Biography information for Chris Elmore","Ogmore","Chris Elmore","49721"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/606855","Ministry of Justice","false","2016-10-25","<p>The Government is investing £1 billion to modernise our world-leading justice system. That means creating a system that is just, proportionate and accessible.</p><p> </p><p>Technology will be at the forefront of our reforms but specific support will be provided to ensure tribunals remain accessible to all and physical hearings will be used to resolve many cases.</p><p> </p><p>The ‘Transforming our Justice System’ consultation is about the administration of justice across all courts and tribunals and not one specific area. My officials are engaging with appropriate stakeholders, including disability groups, on relevant matters. We will consider all submissions before issuing a response in the coming months.</p>","North East Hertfordshire","Sir Oliver Heald",,"2016-10-25T16:56:44.367Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/606855/answer","Biography information for Sir Oliver Heald","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/606855/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/606855/answer",,,,,"54","Justice","Justice","2016-10-20","Social Security Benefits: Disability","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Justice, with reference to the consultation on whether to introduce a new online system for disability benefit appeals, whether the Government (a) took steps to ensure claimants were aware of that consultation, (b) plans to consult with groups representing disabled and ill people and people who claim employment and support allowance, personal independence payment or disability living allowance and (c) will take steps to ensure that the views of claimants are given sufficient weight when deciding whether to proceed with those proposals; and when she plans for the results of that consultation to be released.","false","Biography information for Mr Roger Godsiff","Birmingham, Hall Green","Mr Roger Godsiff","49701"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/606856","Department for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","false","2016-10-28","<p>Since his appointment, my right hon. Friend the Secretary of State for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy has had no discussions with commercial banks and other providers of RFID-enabled cards about incidents of contactless card fraud or their prevention.</p>","Stourbridge","Margot James",,"2016-10-28T13:26:50.143Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/606856/answer","Biography information for Margot James","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/606856/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/606856/answer",,,,,"201","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","2016-10-20","Bank Cards: Fraud","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy, what discussions he has had with commercial banks and other providers of Radio Frequency Identification-enabled cards on (a) incidents of contactless card fraud and (b) prevention of such fraud.","false","Biography information for Nigel Adams","Selby and Ainsty","Nigel Adams","49711"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/606857","HM Treasury","false","2016-10-28","<p>The Government does not hold any data on the recorded incidents of fraud on contactless cards. Industry statistics received from Financial Fraud Action UK indicate that in the first half of 2016 there were £2.9 million losses attributed to fraud on contactless cards compared to a spend of £9.27 billion. According to the industry, fraud on contactless cards accounts for less than 1% of card fraud losses.</p>","Brighton, Kemptown","Simon Kirby",,"2016-10-28T11:16:54.57Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/606857/answer","Biography information for Simon Kirby","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/606857/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/606857/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2016-10-20","Bank Cards: Fraud","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, how many recorded incidents of fraud on contactless cards have been recorded since that technology became available.","false","Biography information for Nigel Adams","Selby and Ainsty","Nigel Adams","49712"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/606858","Department for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","false","2016-10-27","<p>Departmental officials advise that exchange rates are one of the factors which influence future energy imports and their cost. For example, the cost of importing gas is also affected by the availability and cost of a range of gas supplies, infrastructure constraints and global and regional demand. The cost of importing electricity to the UK through its interconnectors with other European countries is also influenced by the electricity generation mix in Europe, by gas, coal and carbon prices and by the level of electricity demand in the UK and other European countries.</p>","Hereford and South Herefordshire","Jesse Norman",,"2016-10-27T11:53:40.68Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/606858/answer","Biography information for Jesse Norman","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/606858/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/606858/answer",,,,,"201","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","2016-10-20","Energy: Imports","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy, what assessment he has made of the effect of trends in the exchange rate on future energy imports; and if he will make a statement.","false","Biography information for Mr Jim Cunningham","Coventry South","Mr Jim Cunningham","49665"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/606859","Department for International Trade","false","2016-10-28","<p>I refer the hon. Member to the answer my hon. Friend, the Minister of State for International Trade (Greg Hands), gave on 21 October to the hon. Member for Kingston upon Hull North (Diana Johnson), UIN 49161.</p>","Wyre Forest","Mark Garnier",,"2016-10-28T13:55:05.027Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/606859/answer","Biography information for Mark Garnier","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/606859/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/606859/answer",,,,,"202","International Trade","International Trade","2016-10-20","Trade Agreements","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for International Trade, whether his Department has begun the formal negotiation process for any new trade deals; and if he will make a statement.","false","Biography information for Mr Jim Cunningham","Coventry South","Mr Jim Cunningham","49650"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/606860","Department for International Trade","false","2016-10-25","<p>The Department for International Trade has already established a strong and capable trade policy team with significant negotiating experience. The team has more than doubled in size since 23 June and is still growing. We will continue to hire the brightest and best talent from within the UK civil service and from elsewhere in order to deliver the best outcomes for the UK.</p>","Chelsea and Fulham","Greg Hands",,"2016-10-25T14:44:17.427Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/606860/answer","Biography information for Greg Hands","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/606860/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/606860/answer",,,,,"202","International Trade","International Trade","2016-10-20","Trade Agreements","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for International Trade, what assessment he has made of the capacity of his Department to negotiate future trade deals with multiple countries and trading blocks at the same time; and if he will make a statement.","false","Biography information for Mr Jim Cunningham","Coventry South","Mr Jim Cunningham","49666"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/606861","Department for International Trade","false","2016-10-25","<p>We are taking advantage of all the opportunities available to us to ensure that Britain becomes the global leader in free trade once we leave the EU, including discussing our future trade relationships with third countries. While we remain a member of the EU, the UK will continue to support the EU’s free trade negotiations.</p>","Chelsea and Fulham","Greg Hands",,"2016-10-25T16:39:31.2Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/606861/answer","Biography information for Greg Hands","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/606861/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/606861/answer",,,,,"202","International Trade","International Trade","2016-10-20","Trade Agreements","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for International Trade, if he will make it his policy only to begin the formal negotiation process on trade deals with non-EU countries once the UK has left the EU; and if he will make a statement.","false","Biography information for Mr Jim Cunningham","Coventry South","Mr Jim Cunningham","49667"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/606862","Department for International Trade","false","2016-10-25","<p>The Prime Minister has been clear, we are not going to provide a running commentary on the negotiations. We recognise the need for a smooth transition as the UK leaves the EU, which minimises disruption to our trading relationships. Ministers and officials in the Department for International Trade are working closely with counterparts across a wide range of markets, in order to promote the UK as a great place to do business and with which to trade. We are taking advantage of all the opportunities available to us to ensure that Britain becomes the global leader in free trade once we leave the EU.</p><p> </p>","Chelsea and Fulham","Greg Hands",,"2016-10-25T16:46:01.473Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/606862/answer","Biography information for Greg Hands","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/606862/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/606862/answer",,,,,"202","International Trade","International Trade","2016-10-20","Trade Agreements","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for International Trade, whether his Department plans to begin the formal negotiation process for trade deals with (a) EU and (b) non-EU countries after the (i) initiation and (ii) conclusion of the Article 50 process; and if he will make a statement.","false","Biography information for Mr Jim Cunningham","Coventry South","Mr Jim Cunningham","49668"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/606863","Department for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","false","2016-10-27","<p>We are working with the US authorities to ensure the restrictions on British lamb are lifted as soon as possible. The US has a longstanding ban on the use of animal lungs as food, but the Scottish haggis industry is working on a US-specific recipe to allow the industry access to the US market at the earliest opportunity.</p>","Camborne and Redruth","George Eustice",,"2016-10-27T13:14:04.317Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/606863/answer","Biography information for George Eustice","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/606863/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/606863/answer",,,,,"13","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","2016-10-20","Meat Products: USA","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs, if she will enter negotiations with her US counterpart to have the ban on British haggis imports to that country lifted once the UK has left the EU.","false","Biography information for Grant Shapps","Welwyn Hatfield","Grant Shapps","49613"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/606864","Department for Exiting the European Union","false","2016-10-27","<p>The Government will ensure that all views can be reflected in our analysis of the options for the UK’s withdrawal from the European Union and we are going to listen and talk to as many organisations, companies and institutions as possible to do this. The Secretary of State for Exiting the European Union visited Northern Ireland on 1 September and I visited on 5-7 October. We engaged with the Northern Ireland Executive and key representatives of businesses and civil society, including roundtables with the retail, hospitality and agrifood sectors and the Northern Ireland Council for Voluntary Action. I have also had discussions with Northern Ireland Executive Ministers for Justice, Communities and Infrastructure. Details of Ministerial meetings will be published in the Department’s Quarterly Transparency Returns, which will be made publicly available on<a href="http://gov.uk/" target="_blank"> GOV.UK</a>.</p><p /><p /> <p> </p>","Worcester","Mr Robin Walker",,"2016-10-27T13:21:54.443Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/606864/answer","Biography information for Mr Robin Walker","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/606864/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/606864/answer",,,,,"203","Exiting the European Union","Exiting the European Union","2016-10-20","Brexit: Northern Ireland","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Exiting the European Union, what discussions his Department has had with (a) East Border Region, (b) Rural Community Networks and (c) other community groups in Northern Ireland as part of the preparations for the negotiations on the UK leaving the EU.","false","Biography information for Jim Shannon","Strangford","Jim Shannon","49619"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/605622","HM Treasury","false","2016-10-25","Inflation statistics are produced independently of government by the Office for National Statistics (ONS). The current main measure of inflation is CPI. This does not include house prices as these are an asset price and in line with international practice are not included in a consumer price index. However, it does include some costs associated with housing, such as rental prices and the costs of renovating and repair and maintenance of homes. The ONS also produces CPIH, which does include housing costs but is currently undergoing development work after the UK Statistics Authority found faults in its production.","Brighton, Kemptown","Simon Kirby",,"2016-10-25T15:44:27.043Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/605622/answer","Biography information for Simon Kirby","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/605622/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/605622/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2016-10-19","Inflation: Housing","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, if he will make it his policy to reflect house prices in the calculation of inflation.","false","Biography information for Dr Andrew Murrison","South West Wiltshire","Dr Andrew Murrison","906805"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/605784","Attorney General","false","2016-10-25","<p>The Serious Fraud Office first received information concerning allegations of bribery and corruption at Rolls Royce in November 2011.</p>","South Swindon","Robert Buckland",,"2016-10-25T09:48:23.3Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/605784/answer","Biography information for Robert Buckland","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/605784/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/605784/answer",,,,,"88","Attorney General","Attorney General","2016-10-19","Rolls Royce: Corruption","1","House of Commons","To ask the Attorney General, on what date the Serious Fraud Office first received information on allegations of bribery and corruption at Rolls Royce.","false","Biography information for Dame Margaret Hodge","Barking","Margaret Hodge","49510"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/605785","Department for Culture, Media and Sport","false","2016-10-24","<p>The last Youth Action Group meeting was 25 Nov 2014. A Youth Action Group Workshop was held on 24 Feb 2015.</p><p> </p><p>Youth Action Group members and meeting participants were drawn from the government departments and national charities that develop policy and deliver programmes for disadvantaged young people. These included the following:</p><ul><li>Government: Cabinet Office, Department for Education, Department for Business, Innovation and Skills, Department for Work and Pensions, Department for Communities and Local Government, Ministry of Justice, Home Office, Department for Health and Ministry of Defence; and</li><li>VCSE sector: The Prince’s Trust, Rathbone, The Foyer Federation, Catch22, Groundwork, Barnardo’s, Youth United, YoungMinds, Brook and Action for Children</li></ul><p> </p><p>There are no current plans for this group to meet.</p><p> </p>","Reading East","Mr Rob Wilson",,"2016-10-24T16:30:43.413Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/605785/answer","Biography information for Mr Rob Wilson","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/605785/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/605785/answer",,,,,"10","Culture, Media and Sport","Culture, Media and Sport","2016-10-19","Youth Action Group","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Culture, Media and Sport, when the Youth Action Group last met; who attended that meeting; and what the current membership of that group is.","false","Biography information for Tim Loughton","East Worthing and Shoreham","Tim Loughton","49475"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/605786","HM Treasury","false","2016-10-24","<p>The government does not hold data on the annual revenue raised from VAT on tourism and related services in the UK and in Scotland. This is because tourism does not follow the standard classification of sectors. For example, revenue raised from travel and hotel accommodation will be a mixture of tourism and non-tourism activity.</p>","Battersea","Jane Ellison",,"2016-10-24T16:12:43.893Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/605786/answer","Biography information for Jane Ellison","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/605786/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/605786/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2016-10-19","Tourism: VAT","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, what the annual revenue raised from VAT on tourism and related services was; and what proportion of this revenue was generated in Scotland for each of the last five years.","false","Biography information for Drew Hendry","Inverness, Nairn, Badenoch and Strathspey","Drew Hendry","49327"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/605787","HM Treasury","false","2016-10-24","<p>The Government keeps all taxes under review, although there are no current plans to review the levels of VAT paid by tourism and hospitality businesses.</p>","Battersea","Jane Ellison",,"2016-10-24T16:10:38.087Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/605787/answer","Biography information for Jane Ellison","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/605787/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/605787/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2016-10-19","Tourism: VAT","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, when his Department plans to review the levels of VAT paid by tourism and hospitality businesses.","false","Biography information for Drew Hendry","Inverness, Nairn, Badenoch and Strathspey","Drew Hendry","49354"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/605788","HM Treasury","false","2016-10-24","<p>The Government keeps all tax rates and thresholds under review.</p>","Battersea","Jane Ellison",,"2016-10-24T14:45:33.623Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/605788/answer","Biography information for Jane Ellison","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/605788/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/605788/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2016-10-19","VAT","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, when his Department plans to review the VAT threshold.","false","Biography information for Drew Hendry","Inverness, Nairn, Badenoch and Strathspey","Drew Hendry","49375"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/605789","HM Treasury","false","2016-10-27","<p>The introduction of the National Living Wage in April 2016 marked an important step towards building an economy that works for everyone. At £7.20, it represented a 50p increase on the National Minimum Wage, and a pay rise for over a million low paid workers across the UK, many of whom will be in low income households.</p><p> </p><p>The estimated impacts of the National Living Wage are set out in the impact assessment and Annex B of the Office of Budget Responsibility’s July Economic and Fiscal Outlook (available at http://www.legislation.gov.uk/ukdsi/2016/9780111141625/impacts/2016/3 and http://budgetresponsibility.org.uk/docs/dlm_uploads/July-2015-EFO-234224.pdf respectively).</p>","Battersea","Jane Ellison",,"2016-10-27T14:01:16Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/605789/answer","Biography information for Jane Ellison","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/605789/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/605789/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2016-10-19","Minimum Wage","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, what assessment he has made of the effect of the increase in the national minimum wage on the incomes of low income households; and if he will make a statement.","false","Biography information for Henry Smith","Crawley","Henry Smith","49383"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/605790","Department for Communities and Local Government","false","2016-10-24","<p>Business rates policy in Scotland is devolved to the Scottish Government. In England, business rates are based on valuations from the Valuation Office Agency and we do not intervene in their independent assessments. We have proposed a £3.4 billion transitional relief scheme for England to ensure that no ratepayer is unfairly penalised by the 2017 revaluation.</p>","Nuneaton","Mr Marcus Jones","49392","2016-10-24T15:48:41.663Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/605790/answer","Biography information for Mr Marcus Jones","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/605790/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/605790/answer",,,,,"7","Communities and Local Government","Communities and Local Government","2016-10-19","Solar Power: Non-domestic Rates","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Communities and Local Government, what assessment he has made of the effect on the UK solar power market of the proposed 2017 business rate rise for organisations investing in roof top solar power for their own consumption.","false","Biography information for Angus Brendan MacNeil","Na h-Eileanan an Iar","Angus Brendan MacNeil","49391"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/605792","Department for Communities and Local Government","false","2016-10-24","<p>Business rates policy in Scotland is devolved to the Scottish Government. In England, business rates are based on valuations from the Valuation Office Agency and we do not intervene in their independent assessments. We have proposed a £3.4 billion transitional relief scheme for England to ensure that no ratepayer is unfairly penalised by the 2017 revaluation.</p>","Nuneaton","Mr Marcus Jones","49391","2016-10-24T15:48:41.617Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/605792/answer","Biography information for Mr Marcus Jones","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/605792/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/605792/answer",,,,,"7","Communities and Local Government","Communities and Local Government","2016-10-19","Solar Power: Non-domestic Rates","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Communities and Local Government, whether he plans to review the planned business rate increase for organisations that seek to own or supply their energy with roof top solar panels in the light of carbon emissions targets agreed at the Paris Climate Change Conference.","false","Biography information for Angus Brendan MacNeil","Na h-Eileanan an Iar","Angus Brendan MacNeil","49392"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/605793","HM Treasury","false","2016-10-27","<p>As is usual in any negotiation, the text of a tax treaty remains confidential between the two governments during the negotiations. It is not therefore possible to comment on the contents of a treaty before it is signed.</p><p> </p><p>The majority of the UK’s double taxation treaties are based on the OECD Model Double Taxation Convention. However, some developing countries prefer to follow the United Nations Model, whose provisions differ in some respects from the OECD Model, including in the “permanent establishment” article. Many of the UK’s treaties with developing countries contain at least some of these provisions. A treaty will be signed only when both governments are satisfied with its contents.</p><p> </p><p>It has long been the UK’s policy to include robust anti-abuse provisions in its tax treaties to ensure that they operate as intended and in particular that residents of third countries cannot indirectly benefit from their provisions.</p><p> </p><p>The text of the new treaty with Malawi was substantively agreed some time ago. However, in August 2016 Malawi raised some further points for consideration, which we will work together on. When that process is complete, and both countries are satisfied with contents of the new treaty, it will be signed and published. Parliament will scrutinise the revised agreement, as part of the affirmative Statutory Instruments procedures, before the treaty can enter into force.</p><p> </p>","Battersea","Jane Ellison","49410 ; 49411 ; 49412 ; 49413","2016-10-27T13:59:51.993Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/605793/answer","Biography information for Jane Ellison","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/605793/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/605793/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2016-10-19","Taxation: Malawi","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, what his Department's policy is on the inclusion of a broad definition of permanent establishment in the UK-Malawi tax treaty.","false","Biography information for Oliver Colvile","Plymouth, Sutton and Devonport","Oliver Colvile","49384"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/605794","HM Treasury","false","2016-10-24","<p>Improving the resilience of the finance sector to risks such as cyber security is a priority for the Government. HM Treasury works closely with the financial regulators to drive this improvement; it is their responsibility to supervise banks’ operations. The Financial Conduct Authority has a specific objective on consumer protection.</p><p> </p><p>The Competition and Markets Authority (CMA) published the final report of its market investigation into retail banking on 9 August 2016. As part of this the CMA requires the nine largest UK banks to develop and adopt an open banking standard for application programming interfaces (APIs) to allow access to customer account information, as set out in the revised Payment Services Directive (PSDII) which will come into force in January 2018. These nine banks are required to deliver open data APIs by Q1 2017, and deliver the full open API banking standard by early 2018. Data protection and cyber security are key considerations in PSDII, and the Government will be consulting on the transposition of this directive shortly.</p>","Brighton, Kemptown","Simon Kirby",,"2016-10-24T13:15:07.897Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/605794/answer","Biography information for Simon Kirby","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/605794/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/605794/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2016-10-19","Bank Services: Fraud","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, what safeguards the Government plans to put in place to protect customers from fraud and cyber security risks if they use new products and services in an open banking environment.","false","Biography information for Chi Onwurah","Newcastle upon Tyne Central","Chi Onwurah","49397"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/605795","HM Treasury","false","2016-10-24","<p>The Government recognises MG Alba's valuable contribution to Gaelic language broadcasting. Although MG ALBA are funded by the Scottish Government, the previous government provided them with two one-off grants that ended in March 2016, for additional support for minority language services. MG ALBA continues to receive public funding from the Scottish Executive. There are no plans for the UK Government to provide further direct funding.</p>","South West Hertfordshire","Mr David Gauke",,"2016-10-24T16:30:44.423Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/605795/answer","Biography information for Mr David Gauke","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/605795/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/605795/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2016-10-19","MG Alba: Finance","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, whether he plans to increase funding for BBC ALBA.","false","Biography information for Angus Brendan MacNeil","Na h-Eileanan an Iar","Angus Brendan MacNeil","49398"
